# SOLAR ENERGY INSTALLATION
# ============================================================
add_lessons('Solar Energy Installation', [
    (1, 'Introduction to Solar Energy', 20,
     'Solar energy is transforming West Africa. Unreliable grid power has made solar the practical choice for millions of homes and businesses.\n\nWHY SOLAR MATTERS IN WEST AFRICA:\nGrid electricity is unreliable in most West African countries.\nDiesel generators are expensive to run and polluting.\nSolar provides clean, quiet, reliable power from abundant sunshine.\nWest Africa receives 4-6 peak sun hours per day — excellent for solar.\nThe solar industry is growing rapidly, creating significant job opportunities.\n\nHOW SOLAR POWER WORKS:\nSolar panels contain photovoltaic (PV) cells.\nWhen sunlight hits the cells, they generate Direct Current (DC) electricity.\nA charge controller manages how the battery is charged.\nA battery stores the electricity for use when the sun is not shining.\nAn inverter converts DC to AC (alternating current) for use with normal appliances.\n\nSOLAR SYSTEM COMPONENTS:\n1. Solar panels: Generate power.\n2. Charge controller: Protects battery from overcharging and over-discharging.\n3. Battery bank: Stores energy. Usually lead-acid or lithium.\n4. Inverter: Converts DC to AC. May be pure sine wave or modified sine wave.\n5. Wiring and fuses: Connects everything safely.\n6. Mounting structure: Holds panels at the correct angle.\n\nSYSTEM TYPES:\nSmall systems: Phone charging, LED lighting, fans. 100-300W panels.\nHome systems: Lighting, TV, fans, small fridge. 300W-2kW panels.\nCommercial systems: Full office or shop power. 2kW-10kW+.\nHybrid systems: Solar plus grid or generator backup.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nIdentify a solar installation in your community.\nWhat components can you identify? How many panels? What is the battery?\nAsk the owner: How much did it cost? What can it power? Is it reliable?\nWrite your observations.'),

    (2, 'System Sizing and Design', 30,
     'A properly sized solar system meets the customer\'s needs without wasting money on excess capacity.\n\nSTEP 1: DETERMINE THE LOAD\nList every appliance to be powered.\nFor each appliance, find or estimate: Power in Watts, Hours per day used.\nCalculate: Watt-hours per day for each appliance.\nExample:\nLED lights (4 x 10W, 6 hours): 240 Wh\nTV 50W (5 hours): 250 Wh\nFan 50W (8 hours): 400 Wh\nPhone charging (20W, 2 hours): 40 Wh\nTOTAL DAILY LOAD: 930 Wh (approximately 1 kWh)\n\nSTEP 2: CALCULATE PANEL SIZE\nDivide daily load by peak sun hours (use 4-5 hours for West Africa).\n930 Wh divided by 4.5 hours = 207W of panels needed.\nAdd 25% safety factor: 207 times 1.25 = 258W.\nChoose: 2 x 150W panels = 300W (nearest practical size).\n\nSTEP 3: CALCULATE BATTERY SIZE\nBattery must store enough for cloudy days.\nFor 2 days autonomy with 50% depth of discharge:\nBattery capacity = 930 Wh times 2 days divided by 0.5 (depth of discharge) = 3,720 Wh.\nIn amp-hours at 12V: 3,720 divided by 12 = 310 Ah.\nChoose: 2 x 200Ah batteries in parallel = 400 Ah (nearest practical).\n\nSTEP 4: SELECT CHARGE CONTROLLER\nMust handle panel output current.\n300W panels at 12V system = 25A. Choose 30A or 40A controller.\nPWM controllers: Simpler, cheaper.\nMPPT controllers: 15-30% more efficient. Better for larger systems.\n\nSTEP 5: SELECT INVERTER\nMust handle the peak load (all appliances running simultaneously).\nAdd up power of all appliances: 4+50+50+20 = 124W typical.\nAdd startup surge (motors can draw 3x rated power on startup).\nChoose inverter with 20% headroom: In this case a 300W inverter is adequate.\nPure sine wave inverter: Works with all appliances. More expensive but required for sensitive electronics.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nDesign a solar system for: 6 LED lights (10W each, 5 hours), 1 TV (60W, 4 hours), 2 phone chargers (15W each, 2 hours), 1 fan (45W, 8 hours).\nCalculate: Daily load, panel size, battery capacity, controller rating, inverter size.'),

    (3, 'Installation and Wiring', 30,
     'Safe installation is critical. Poor wiring causes fires, system failure and can kill.\n\nSAFETY FIRST:\nSolar panels generate electricity as soon as sunlight hits them — they cannot be switched off.\nAlways cover panels before working on wiring.\nBatteries store significant energy and can cause burns or fire if short-circuited.\nUse insulated tools. Never short-circuit battery terminals.\nInstall fuses close to all positive battery connections.\n\nMOUNTING PANELS:\nRoof mounting: Ensure roof structure can bear the weight (approximately 15-20 kg per panel).\nGround mounting: Requires concrete footings for stability.\nOptimum tilt angle: Approximately equal to your latitude (Freetown is 8° N, so approximately 8-15° tilt).\nFace panels toward the equator (south in West Africa — face panels south).\nEnsure no shading from trees, buildings or other panels — even partial shade reduces output significantly.\n\nWIRING THE SYSTEM:\nUse correct cable sizes to minimise resistance (power loss) and heat.\nPanel to charge controller: Use solar cable (UV resistant). Size for short-circuit current.\nBattery to controller: Same size as panel cable or larger.\nBattery to inverter: Largest cable in the system (highest current).\nKeep cable runs as short as possible.\n\nFUSES AND CIRCUIT PROTECTION:\nFuse between each panel string and the controller.\nFuse between battery positive and controller.\nFuse (or circuit breaker) between battery and inverter.\nSize fuses appropriately — slightly above the expected current, not oversized.\n\nCONNECTING BATTERIES:\nSeries connection: Increases voltage (two 12V = 24V). Capacity stays the same.\nParallel connection: Increases capacity (two 200Ah = 400Ah). Voltage stays the same.\nMost small home systems: 12V with parallel batteries.\nLarger systems: 24V or 48V for efficiency.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nDraw a wiring diagram for a complete 12V solar system: 2 panels, MPPT controller, 2 batteries in parallel, 300W inverter.\nLabel all fuses, cable sizes and connections.\nList the tools and safety equipment needed for this installation.'),

    (4, 'Maintenance and Fault Finding', 20,
     'Solar systems require minimal maintenance but problems do occur. A systematic approach diagnoses and fixes them quickly.\n\nROUTINE MAINTENANCE:\nMonthly:\nClean panels with clean water and soft cloth. Dirty panels lose 15-25% output.\nCheck all cable connections are tight and not corroded.\nCheck battery terminals — clean off any corrosion with bicarbonate of soda solution.\nCheck battery water level (lead-acid batteries only) — top up with distilled water if low.\nCheck inverter vents are not blocked.\n\nQuarterly:\nCheck mounting structure for looseness or corrosion.\nRecord battery voltage under load. Declining voltage suggests battery degradation.\nCheck charge controller display readings.\n\nCOMMON FAULTS AND DIAGNOSIS:\n\nNO OUTPUT FROM PANELS:\nCheck: Is there sunlight? Are panels covered?\nCheck: Fuse in panel circuit.\nMeasure panel output voltage (should match specification on label).\nCheck connections at controller.\n\nBATTERY NOT CHARGING:\nCheck: Charge controller display (what does it show?).\nMeasure panel voltage at controller input.\nCheck fuses.\nCheck charge controller settings (battery type must match).\n\nINVERTER NOT WORKING:\nCheck: Battery voltage (if too low, inverter shuts down automatically).\nCheck: Fuse between battery and inverter.\nCheck: Inverter overload indicator (too much load).\nCheck: Temperature (inverter overheats if ventilation is blocked).\n\nSHORT BATTERY LIFE:\nCauses: Overcharging (controller fault), over-discharging (using too much power), old batteries, wrong battery type.\nSolution: Check charge controller settings. Reduce load or add panels and batteries.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nGiven a solar system that powers lights but the inverter shuts down after 30 minutes:\nList all possible causes in order of likelihood.\nDescribe the tests you would perform to diagnose the fault.\nWhat is the most likely single cause and how would you fix it?'),

    (5, 'Solar Business and Career', 15,
     'Solar energy is one of the fastest-growing industries in West Africa. The career opportunities are significant and growing.\n\nSERVICES TO OFFER:\nResidential installation: Homes with unreliable grid power.\nCommercial installation: Shops, offices, churches, mosques.\nSchool and health facility solar: NGOs often fund these — can be large contracts.\nSolar repair and maintenance contracts: Recurring income.\nSolar product sales: Sell panels, batteries and accessories with installation.\n\nTHE MARKET IN WEST AFRICA:\nMillions of homes have no reliable electricity.\nPetrol and diesel costs are high and rising.\nSolar prices have fallen 90% in the last decade — now accessible for ordinary households.\nGovernments and NGOs actively support solar expansion.\nFinancing options (solar loans, pay-as-you-go) are expanding the market to lower-income customers.\n\nPRICING SOLAR INSTALLATIONS:\nComponents: At cost plus 20-25% markup.\nInstallation labour: Per day or per system.\nExample small home system (300W):\nPanels: Le 450,000\nBattery (200Ah): Le 350,000\nController: Le 80,000\nInverter (300W): Le 120,000\nCables, fuses, mounts: Le 80,000\nTotal components: Le 1,080,000\nWith 22% markup: Le 1,317,600\nInstallation labour: Le 200,000\nTOTAL TO CUSTOMER: approximately Le 1,500,000\n\nQUALITY AND REPUTATION:\nIn solar, quality failures destroy your reputation overnight.\nUse quality components — cheap panels and batteries fail quickly.\nProvide written warranty and a service contact for issues.\nMaintenance contracts provide recurring income and keep you connected to your customers.\n\nCERTIFICATIONS:\nRenewable energy certifications are available online from Coursera, edX and others.\nSome manufacturers (Victron, Outback) offer installer training.\nThese differentiate you from untrained competitors.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nResearch solar panel and battery prices in your local market today.\nBuild a complete price list for three system sizes: Small (150W), medium (500W), large (1.5kW).\nIdentify three potential customers in your community who would benefit from solar.\nHow would you approach them?'),
])

# ============================================================
# PHONE AND ELECTRONICS REPAIRS
# ============================================================
add_lessons('Phone and Electronics Repairs', [
    (1, 'Introduction to Smartphone Repair', 20,
     'Smartphone repair is one of the fastest-growing and most accessible trades in West Africa. Virtually everyone has a phone. All phones break.\n\nTHE OPPORTUNITY:\nOver 500 million smartphones are in use across Africa.\nSmartphone penetration is growing rapidly.\nAccidents (cracked screens, water damage, battery failure) are inevitable.\nRepair costs a fraction of replacement — customers prefer it.\nLow startup cost for the trade.\n\nPHONE REPAIR TOOLS:\nPrecision screwdriver set: Pentalobe (for iPhones), Phillips #000, Torx, Tri-wing.\nPlastic opening tools: Pry bars and picks to open phone cases without damage.\nSuction cup: For lifting screens.\nHeat gun or warm pad: Softens adhesive for screen removal.\nTweezers (fine point): For small components.\nAntistatic mat and wrist strap: Protects phone from static damage.\nMagnifying glass or headband loupe: For small components.\nMultimeter: For testing voltages and continuity.\nSoldering iron (for advanced repair): 65W with fine tip. Flux and solder.\n\nPHONE ANATOMY:\nDisplay assembly: Screen, touch digitiser, sometimes front camera.\nBattery: Lithium polymer (LiPo). Non-removable in most modern phones.\nLogic board (motherboard): CPU, RAM, storage, power management.\nCharging port: Often fails from repeated plugging and movement.\nSpeakers and microphone.\nCamera modules: Front and rear.\nBack cover: Glass or plastic.\n\nSAFETY:\nBatteries can catch fire if punctured, short-circuited or improperly heated.\nNever use a sharp tool near the battery.\nAlways power off the phone before opening.\nDisconnect battery before working on other components.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nDisassemble an old or broken phone (not a customer\'s working phone).\nIdentify: Battery, display assembly, charging port, cameras, speaker, SIM tray.\nReassemble and check all screws are returned to correct holes.\nDocument: What tools were needed? What challenges did you encounter?'),

    (2, 'Screen Replacement', 30,
     'Cracked and broken screens are the most common phone repair. Learning this skill opens your business immediately.\n\nWHY SCREENS CRACK:\nDrop damage: Most common. Impact cracks glass or LCD beneath.\nPressure damage: Sitting on phone, heavy objects on screen.\nTouch issues without visible crack: Digitiser failure.\n\nTYPES OF DISPLAYS:\nLCD (Liquid Crystal Display): Common on budget and mid-range phones.\nConsists of: LCD panel + touch digitiser + glass (may be separate layers).\nOLED/AMOLED: Higher-end phones (Samsung, iPhone). Thinner, better colours.\nSome screens are sold as complete assemblies (all layers together) — easier to replace.\nSome are sold as glass only (requires bonding equipment to separate layers) — more advanced.\n\nSCREEN REPLACEMENT PROCESS:\n\n1. PREPARE:\nConfirm screen type and order correct replacement.\nPower off phone. Remove SIM tray.\nPrepare tools: Opening picks, suction cup, heat gun, screwdrivers.\n\n2. OPEN PHONE:\nHeat edges gently (50-60°C) to soften adhesive.\nApply suction cup near bottom edge. Apply slight pull.\nInsert plastic pick into gap between screen and frame.\nSlide pick around edges to release adhesive. Go slowly — cable connections are near edges.\n\n3. DISCONNECT BATTERY FIRST:\nAfter opening, find battery connector. Disconnect before anything else.\nThis prevents short circuits if tools contact board.\n\n4. DISCONNECT SCREEN:\nFind display flex cable connector on motherboard.\nSome phones have 1 connector; others have 2 (display + digitiser).\nUnscrew connector bracket. Prise connector gently upward.\n\n5. FIT NEW SCREEN:\nConnect new screen to motherboard. Boot to test before sealing.\nConfirm: Display works, touch works, no dead spots.\n\n6. SEAL AND CLOSE:\nApply new adhesive strip or use original adhesive if usable.\nReplace screws. Apply light pressure to bond adhesive.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nReplace the screen on a broken or practice phone.\nDocument every step with photos.\nTest all functions after assembly: Screen display, touch, front camera, sensors.'),

    (3, 'Battery Replacement and Charging Faults', 25,
     'Battery problems are the second most common repair. Understanding batteries makes you a complete phone repairer.\n\nBATTERY DEGRADATION:\nLiPo batteries lose capacity over time.\nAfter 500-800 charge cycles, capacity falls to approximately 80% of original.\nSymptoms: Battery drains quickly, phone shuts off at 15-20%, phone gets hot.\nTest: Most Android phones have battery health information in settings or via *#*#4636#*#* code.\niPhones: Settings > Battery > Battery Health.\n\nSWOLLEN BATTERIES:\nA swollen battery is a safety emergency.\nSwelling indicates internal gas from chemical breakdown.\nRisk of rupture and fire.\nReplace immediately. Do not charge a swollen battery.\nDo not puncture — flammable gas inside.\n\nBATTERY REPLACEMENT:\nMost modern phones have batteries glued in.\nApply heat (45-50°C) to soften adhesive.\nUse plastic tools only near battery — puncture causes fire.\nSlide thin plastic card under battery to lift adhesive.\nConnect new battery. Test boot.\nReassemble.\n\nCHARGING PROBLEMS:\n\nPHONE WON\'T CHARGE:\nCheck 1: Try a different cable. Most charging problems are cable failure.\nCheck 2: Try a different charger.\nCheck 3: Inspect charging port with magnifying glass — bent pins, debris inside.\nClean port: Use non-conductive tool (plastic or wooden toothpick). Remove lint carefully.\nCheck 4: If cleaning and cable replacement do not work, charging port requires replacement.\n\nCHARGING PORT REPLACEMENT:\nCharging port is typically on a small flex cable or board.\nUnplug phone, disconnect battery.\nUnscrew and unplug old charging port.\nFit new port. Reconnect and test before sealing.\n\nFAST CHARGING NOT WORKING:\nEnsure cable and charger both support fast charging (Quick Charge or USB-C PD).\nSome phones need to cool down before fast charging engages.\nCheck settings: Fast charging may be disabled.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCheck battery health on three different phones.\nClean the charging port on a phone that has debris (use compressed air or plastic toothpick).\nTest charging with multiple cables and chargers to diagnose whether fault is cable, charger or port.'),

    (4, 'Software Issues and Data Recovery', 20,
     'Not all phone problems are hardware. Software faults are very common and often simpler to resolve.\n\nCOMMON SOFTWARE PROBLEMS:\n\nPHONE WON\'T TURN ON:\nHold power button for 10-15 seconds (force restart).\nIf no response: Plug into power. Wait 10 minutes. Try again.\nIf still no response: Check for hardware fault.\n\nPHONE STUCK ON LOGO:\nForce restart (power + volume down held together on most Android).\nIf unsuccessful: Boot into recovery mode (power + volume up on most Android).\nIn recovery: Try "Wipe cache partition" — fixes many software problems without data loss.\nIf still stuck: Factory reset (loses all data — warn customer first).\n\nFORGOTTEN SCREEN LOCK PASSWORD:\nAndroid: Multiple wrong attempts may allow Google account unlock.\nOr: Boot into recovery, factory reset (data loss).\niPhone: Connect to computer with iTunes or Finder, put into recovery mode, restore.\nData will be lost unless iCloud backup was enabled.\n\nVIRUSES AND MALWARE (ANDROID):\nSymptoms: Excessive battery drain, unexpected ads, apps opening alone, data usage spikes.\nSolutions: Install reputable antivirus (Malwarebytes). Identify and uninstall suspicious apps.\nNuclear option: Factory reset.\n\nDATA RECOVERY:\nIf phone is damaged but storage may be intact:\nAttempt to boot in safe mode.\nConnect to computer and copy files.\nFor physically damaged phones: Advanced recovery services use chip reading equipment.\nAlways ask customers to authorise and back up data before any repair.\n\nINSTALLING CUSTOM FIRMWARE:\nSometimes official software updates break phones.\nCustom recovery and clean ROM installation can restore functionality.\nRequires research for specific phone model.\nRisk: If done incorrectly, phone becomes permanently unusable (bricked).\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPerform a factory reset on an old Android phone (ensure no data to lose first).\nSet it up from scratch.\nInstall a security app and run a scan.\nBack up contacts and photos to Google account.'),

    (5, 'Running a Phone Repair Business', 15,
     'Phone repair is one of the best small businesses in West Africa — high demand, low overheads, fast turnaround.\n\nSETTING UP:\nLocation: A busy street, near a market or transport hub.\nDisplay broken phones attractively to show your services.\nKeep your workspace clean and organised — this builds customer confidence.\nInvest in basic diagnostic equipment first, advanced tools as business grows.\n\nSERVICE MENU AND PRICING:\nScreen replacement (budget phone): Le 80,000-150,000 depending on phone model.\nScreen replacement (flagship): Le 200,000-500,000.\nBattery replacement: Le 40,000-120,000.\nCharging port: Le 30,000-80,000.\nSoftware repair/unlock: Le 20,000-50,000.\nWater damage assessment and repair: Le 30,000 assessment, variable repair cost.\n\nDIAGNOSIS FEE:\nCharge a diagnostic fee for assessing faults.\nDeduct from repair cost if customer proceeds.\nProtects your time when customers decide not to repair.\n\nPARTS SOURCING:\nQuality of parts determines quality of repair and your reputation.\nBudget vs OEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer) parts.\nBudget screens: Cheaper but lower quality, shorter life — may damage your reputation.\nOEM or high-quality aftermarket: Better but more expensive — your reputation benefits.\nTell customers the difference and let them choose.\n\nDATA RESPONSIBILITY:\nCustomers\' phones contain personal, private information.\nNever access data unless necessary for the repair.\nNever copy or share customer data.\nAlways get written authorisation for data backup or reset.\nThis is both ethical and builds trust.\n\nGROWING THE BUSINESS:\nAdd accessories sales: Cases, screen protectors, chargers, earphones.\nOffer buyback and refurbishment: Buy broken phones, fix and resell.\nBrand partnerships: Authorised service centre status from manufacturers.\nOnline presence: WhatsApp and social media showing your repairs builds reach.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCreate a complete price list for your most common 10 repairs.\nSet up a simple repair tracking system: Customer name, phone model, fault reported, price quoted, deposit paid, completion date.\nPractice: Greet a customer, diagnose a fault, explain the repair clearly, quote the price professionally.'),
])

# ============================================================
# CATERING AND FOOD PROCESSING
# ============================================================
add_lessons('Catering and Food Processing', [
    (1, 'Food Safety and Hygiene', 20,
     'Food safety is not optional. A caterer who makes people sick destroys their business and may face legal consequences.\n\nWHY FOOD SAFETY MATTERS:\nFoodborne illness causes vomiting, diarrhea and fever.\nSevere cases cause hospitalisation or death.\nIn West Africa, cholera, typhoid, salmonella and E.coli are real risks from poorly handled food.\nOne outbreak of illness from your food ends your business permanently.\n\nFOOD SAFETY PRINCIPLES:\n\nPERSONAL HYGIENE:\nWash hands thoroughly: Before handling food, after toilet, after handling raw meat, after touching face or hair.\nUse soap and clean water for at least 20 seconds.\nKeep nails short and clean.\nWear clean clothing. Use apron.\nKeep hair covered.\nDo not handle food if you are sick, have open wounds or infections.\n\nTEMPERATURE CONTROL:\nBacteria multiply rapidly between 5°C and 63°C (the danger zone).\nHot food must be kept above 63°C.\nCold food must be kept below 5°C (refrigerated).\nNever leave cooked food at room temperature for more than 2 hours.\nIn hot West African conditions, this time is even shorter.\n\nCROSS-CONTAMINATION:\nRaw meat, fish and poultry must never contact ready-to-eat foods.\nUse separate chopping boards and utensils for raw and cooked food.\nWash surfaces and boards between uses.\nStore raw meat below cooked food in the refrigerator.\n\nCLEANING AND SANITISING:\nCleaning removes dirt and grease.\nSanitising kills bacteria after cleaning.\nDo both. In sequence. Cleaning first, then sanitise.\nUse clean water. Change washing water frequently.\n\nFOOD STORAGE:\nLabel and date all stored food.\nFirst In, First Out (FIFO): Use older stock before newer.\nKeep dry goods in sealed containers — prevents pests.\nCheck food for signs of spoilage before using: Smell, colour, texture.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nAudit your kitchen or cooking area.\nIdentify five food safety risks present.\nFor each risk: What is the danger? What is the solution?\nImplement the solutions immediately.'),

    (2, 'Menu Planning and Costing', 25,
     'A profitable catering business is built on well-planned menus with accurately calculated costs.\n\nMENU PLANNING PRINCIPLES:\nCater to your market: What food do your customers want?\nBalance: Offer variety but not so many items that quality suffers.\nSeasonal: Use ingredients that are fresh and cheap in season.\nPractical: Can you prepare this quantity in your kitchen with your equipment?\nProfitable: Every menu item must make money.\n\nCOSTING A RECIPE:\nFor each dish:\n1. List every ingredient.\n2. Calculate the cost of the exact quantity used per portion.\n3. Add all ingredient costs = food cost per portion.\n4. Add packaging if served to-go.\n5. Food cost should be 25-35% of selling price.\n\nEXAMPLE — JOLLOF RICE (per 10 portions):\nRice 1kg: Le 18,000\nTomatoes/paste: Le 8,000\nOnions: Le 3,000\nSeasoning: Le 2,000\nCooking oil: Le 4,000\nFuel (wood/gas): Le 3,000\nTOTAL FOR 10: Le 38,000\nFood cost per portion: Le 3,800\nSelling price (food cost = 30%): Le 3,800 divided by 0.30 = Le 12,667\nRound to: Le 13,000 per portion\n\nFACTOR IN LABOUR:\nYour time preparing food has a cost.\nIf rice takes 2 hours and you value your time at Le 15,000/hour, that is Le 30,000 labour for 10 portions.\nLabour per portion: Le 3,000.\nSelling price including labour: Le 16,000-17,000.\n\nSTANDARDISE YOUR RECIPES:\nWrite down exact quantities for every dish.\nThis ensures consistent quality and consistent cost.\nWhen you know your cost, you know your profit.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nChoose three dishes you cook.\nCost each recipe per portion using the method above.\nCalculate the selling price at a 30% food cost ratio.\nCompare to what you currently charge or plan to charge.'),

    (3, 'Event Catering Operations', 25,
     'Event catering — weddings, funerals, naming ceremonies, graduations — is the most profitable segment of the catering industry.\n\nTYPES OF EVENTS:\nWeddings: Highest budget. Often 100-500+ guests. Multiple courses.\nFunerals: Large gatherings. Simple, hearty food in large quantity.\nNaming ceremonies: Family celebrations. Traditional foods.\nGraduations: Often office catering or small gatherings.\nCorporate events: Office lunches, meetings, product launches.\n\nSECURING EVENT CONTRACTS:\nBuild relationships with event planners, venue owners, church administrators.\nOffer tastings: Let potential clients sample your cooking.\nHave references: Satisfied past clients.\nPresent professionally: Written quotation, menu card, contract.\n\nEVENT COSTING:\nAlways provide a written quotation.\nInclude: Food cost, packaging, staffing, transport, equipment hire, your profit.\nTake 50% deposit when contract is signed.\nBalance before or on delivery.\n\nPRE-EVENT PLANNING:\nMenu confirmed in writing.\nIngredient list prepared.\nShopping scheduled (1-2 days before for fresh items).\nCooking schedule: What can be prepared in advance? What must be fresh?\nEquipment and serving items confirmed.\nTransport to venue arranged.\nStaff briefed on duties.\n\nON-SITE CATERING:\nArrive at venue well in advance.\nSet up serving area before guests arrive.\nMaintain temperature of hot food (chafing dishes, hot boxes).\nMonitor food levels and restock service as needed.\nMaintain hygiene standards throughout.\nClear up efficiently — your reputation extends to how you leave the venue.\n\nFOOD PROCESSING FOR SALE:\nPreserved foods: Smoked fish, dried pepper, fermented locust beans (dawadawa).\nPackaged foods: Peanut butter, chilli oil, seasoning blends.\nBaked goods: Bread, cakes, chin-chin, puff-puff.\nPack attractively with labels showing: Product name, ingredients, date made, your contact.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPlan a menu for a naming ceremony for 50 people.\nCost the menu completely: Food, packaging, staffing, transport.\nPrepare a written quotation as if presenting to a client.\nCalculate: What is your profit if all goes to plan?'),

    (4, 'Food Preservation and Processing', 20,
     'Food processing extends shelf life and creates products that can be sold beyond the immediate catering market.\n\nWHY FOOD PROCESSING:\nFresh food spoils quickly in West African heat.\nPreserved foods can be sold further from the production point.\nPackaged processed food commands higher prices.\nProcessed food can be sold online and shipped.\n\nPRESERVATION METHODS:\n\nDRYING:\nSun drying: Traditional method. Effective for fish, pepper, cassava, fruit.\nRequires: Clean drying racks, protection from insects, covered during rain.\nSolar dryers: Enclosed frames with transparent cover. Faster and more hygienic.\nOven drying: More controlled but uses fuel.\n\nSMOKING:\nPreserves meat and fish. Adds flavour.\nTraditional smoking kilns or modern drum smokers.\nSmoked fish commands premium prices.\n\nPICKLING:\nAcid (vinegar) preserves vegetables and peppers.\nBottled pickled vegetables, peppers and okra have growing market.\n\nSUGAR PRESERVATION:\nHigh sugar concentration prevents bacterial growth.\nJams, jellies, fruit preserves.\nWest African fruits: Mango jam, pineapple jam, baobab products.\n\nFERMENTATION:\nDawadawa (locust bean): Fermented for seasoning. High value product.\nOgi/akamu: Fermented maize porridge. Popular weaning food.\nTraditional beverages: Ginger beer, zobo (hibiscus drink).\n\nPACKAGING AND LABELLING:\nHygienically sealed packaging extends shelf life.\nProfessional labels build brand identity.\nLabels must include: Product name, ingredients, allergens, manufacturing date, best before date, producer contact.\nGet feedback on packaging: Does it look professional? Does it protect the product?\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nMake one preserved food product: Smoked fish, dried pepper, pickled vegetables, or jam.\nPackage it professionally.\nCalculate the full cost and appropriate selling price.\nTest: Present to five people for honest feedback on taste, packaging and price point.'),

    (5, 'Building a Catering Business', 15,
     'A catering business built on quality food, reliability and professionalism grows through word of mouth.\n\nSTARTING YOUR CATERING BUSINESS:\nStart from home: Low overhead to begin.\nBuild your menu of 5-10 signature dishes you excel at.\nCook for friends and family first: Build your confidence and reputation.\nTake your first paid event as a learning experience, not a money-making exercise.\n\nESSENTIAL EQUIPMENT:\nLarge cooking pots (appropriate sizes).\nChafing dishes and fuel for keeping food hot at events.\nServing spoons, ladles, tongs.\nFood containers for transport and storage.\nCoolers for cold food transport.\n\nMAINTAIN HYGIENE STANDARDS:\nObtain food handler certification if available in your area.\nGet your kitchen inspected if possible.\nBuild a reputation for safe, clean food.\n\nMARKETING:\nCreate a WhatsApp Business profile with photos of your food.\nFacebook and Instagram for reach.\nBusiness cards and a simple menu card.\nOffer corporate clients a weekly or monthly meal service.\nRegular daily prepared meals: Office workers and busy families buy daily lunch.\n\nPRICING FOR EVENTS:\nAlways written quotation.\nAlways 50% deposit.\nBe honest about what is included: Food only? Service staff? Equipment?\nExtra charges: Overtime, additional distance, late bookings.\n\nGROWING THE BUSINESS:\nHire helpers for large events.\nRent or hire specialist equipment as needed before buying.\nSpecialise: Corporate catering, wedding catering, daily meals delivery.\nDevelop a catering kit you can transport efficiently.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCreate your catering business profile:\nYour three signature dishes.\nYour service area.\nYour pricing for 50, 100 and 200 person events.\nYour terms and conditions (deposit, cancellation policy).\nThis is your catering business plan.'),
])

# ============================================================
# REFRIGERATION AND AIR CONDITIONING
# ============================================================
add_lessons('Refrigeration and Air Conditioning', [
    (1, 'Refrigeration and AC Fundamentals', 20,
     'Refrigeration and air conditioning are essential in West Africa\'s hot climate. The market for installation, repair and maintenance is enormous and growing.\n\nTHE REFRIGERATION CYCLE:\nRefrigeration works by transferring heat from inside the unit to outside.\nThe refrigerant is the working fluid that carries this heat.\n\nFOUR MAIN COMPONENTS:\n1. Compressor: Compresses refrigerant gas, raising its temperature and pressure.\n2. Condenser: Hot high-pressure gas releases heat to the outside air and becomes liquid.\n3. Expansion valve: Liquid refrigerant passes through a restriction, dropping pressure and temperature rapidly.\n4. Evaporator: Cold low-pressure liquid absorbs heat from the space being cooled, becoming gas.\nThe compressor then draws the gas in and the cycle repeats.\n\nREFRIGERANTS:\nR134a: Common in domestic refrigerators and car AC.\nR22: Old refrigerant. Being phased out globally due to ozone depletion.\nR410A: Common in modern air conditioners.\nR32: Newer, more environmentally friendly AC refrigerant.\nHandling refrigerants requires care: Never release to atmosphere (illegal and harmful).\n\nTYPES OF SYSTEMS:\nDomestic refrigerator: Self-contained. Single compressor.\nCommercial refrigeration: Walk-in cold rooms, display chillers.\nSplit air conditioner: Outdoor unit (compressor and condenser) connected to indoor unit (evaporator and fan).\nWindow AC: Self-contained unit fitted in a wall or window.\nCentral AC: Ducted system for large buildings.\n\nTOOLS REQUIRED:\nManifold gauge set: Reads high and low side pressures.\nRefrigerant recovery machine: Removes refrigerant safely.\nElectronic leak detector: Finds refrigerant leaks.\nVacuum pump: Removes air and moisture from system before charging.\nRefrigerant scales: For accurate charging.\nMultimeter: Electrical testing.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nIdentify the four main components on a domestic refrigerator.\nLocate: Compressor (bottom or back), condenser coils, evaporator coils inside fridge, capillary tube or expansion device.\nWith a multimeter, check if the compressor motor windings have continuity.'),

    (2, 'Domestic Refrigerator Repair', 25,
     'Domestic refrigerator repair is the starting point for most refrigeration technicians.\n\nNOT COOLING FAULTS:\n\nCOMPRESSOR NOT RUNNING:\nCheck: Power supply to fridge. Check thermostat (disconnect and bridge - if compressor starts, thermostat is faulty).\nCheck: Overload protector (small component clipped to compressor). If open circuit, replace.\nCheck: Start relay (rattles like a marble inside if dead). Replace.\nIf none of these: Test compressor windings with multimeter. If short or open, compressor needs replacing.\n\nCOMPRESSOR RUNS BUT NOT COOLING:\nCheck: Condenser coils — dirty/dusty coils cannot release heat. Clean with brush and compressed air.\nCheck: Evaporator fan running (in fridge with fan). If not, ice may have blocked it.\nCheck: Door seals — if damaged, warm air enters constantly.\nCheck: Refrigerant — if system is low on refrigerant, cooling is poor. Requires gauges to check.\n\nFROSTING PROBLEMS:\nExcessive frost on evaporator: Defrost timer or heater fault (frost-free fridges).\nManual defrost: Unplug fridge, allow to defrost completely, check defrost heater and timer.\nIce forming in freezer only/not in fridge section: Air damper door stuck or broken.\n\nNOISY FRIDGE:\nRattling: Compressor mounting springs worn. Pipes touching cabinet.\nLoud humming: Compressor start winding problem or low voltage.\nClicking repeatedly: Compressor trying and failing to start — check overload, start relay.\n\nWATER LEAKING INSIDE FRIDGE:\nDefrost drain blocked with ice or debris.\nLocate drain hole at back of fridge interior. Clear with warm water and thin wire.\n\nGAS LEAKS:\nRefrigerant leak causes gradual loss of cooling over weeks or months.\nLocate leak with electronic leak detector or soap solution.\nRepair leak by brazing (welding small pipes). Evacuate and recharge with correct refrigerant quantity.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nDiagnose a domestic refrigerator with a known fault.\nCheck compressor, thermostat, overload protector, start relay, condenser cleanliness.\nDocument your diagnostic process and findings.'),

    (3, 'Air Conditioning Installation and Maintenance', 30,
     'Split air conditioners are the most common type installed across West Africa.\n\nSPLIT AC COMPONENTS:\nIndoor unit: Fan coil unit. Contains evaporator, fan, air filter, control board.\nOutdoor unit: Condensing unit. Contains compressor, condenser coil, condenser fan.\nConnecting pipes: Two copper pipes (liquid line and suction line) carry refrigerant.\nDrain pipe: Removes condensate water from indoor unit.\nElectrical cable: Powers outdoor unit from indoor unit.\n\nSIZING AN AIR CONDITIONER:\nAC capacity measured in BTU/hr or kW.\nAs a rough guide: 9,000 BTU for approximately 10-15 sqm room.\n12,000 BTU for 15-20 sqm. 18,000 BTU for 20-30 sqm.\nFactors affecting sizing: Sun exposure, number of occupants, insulation, ceiling height.\nUndersizing: AC runs continuously and never reaches temperature.\nOversizing: Short cycles, poor humidity control, higher cost.\n\nINSTALLATION PROCESS:\n1. Mount indoor unit bracket on wall (1.8-2m high).\n2. Thread pipes through wall.\n3. Mount outdoor unit (on bracket or concrete pad). Secure firmly.\n4. Connect refrigerant pipes: Flare connections or brazing.\n5. Connect electrical cable.\n6. Connect drain pipe. Route drain to outside.\n7. Vacuum the system with vacuum pump for minimum 30 minutes (removes air and moisture).\n8. Open service valves (on outdoor unit) to release factory charge into system.\n9. Test operation: Check temperatures, pressures, check for leaks.\n\nROUTINE MAINTENANCE (every 3-6 months):\nClean air filter: Wash with water, dry before replacing.\nClean evaporator coils (indoor): Use coil cleaner spray.\nClean condenser coils (outdoor): Hose with water from inside out.\nCheck drain is flowing freely.\nCheck refrigerant pressures.\nCheck electrical connections.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPerform a maintenance service on any available split AC.\nClean filter, clean indoor coil, clear drain, clean outdoor condenser.\nMeasure indoor and outdoor air temperatures before and after cleaning.\nNote the improvement in performance.'),

    (4, 'Refrigerant Handling and Leak Detection', 20,
     'Correct refrigerant handling is required by law in most countries and protects the environment.\n\nWHY REFRIGERANT HANDLING MATTERS:\nRefrigerants cause ozone layer damage and contribute to global warming.\nR22 has been banned or restricted in many countries for this reason.\nReleasing refrigerant to atmosphere is illegal in most jurisdictions.\nProper recovery and recycling is required.\n\nPRESSURE GAUGES AND CHARGING:\nManifold gauge set has two gauges: High pressure (red, high side) and low pressure (blue, low side).\nConnections: Blue hose to low side service valve, red to high side, yellow to refrigerant cylinder.\nNormal operating pressures vary by refrigerant — always know your system\'s refrigerant type.\nFor R22 split AC: Low side approximately 70 psi, high side approximately 200-250 psi.\nFor R410A split AC: Low side approximately 120 psi, high side approximately 350-400 psi.\n\nREFRIGERANT RECOVERY:\nBefore opening any system, recover refrigerant with a recovery machine.\nRefrigerant is stored in recovery cylinders.\nNever vent to atmosphere.\n\nCHARGING A SYSTEM:\nEvacuate system with vacuum pump.\nVerify vacuum holds (no leaks).\nConnect refrigerant cylinder to yellow hose.\nOpen valve slowly. Charge by weight (most accurate) or by pressure.\nCharge to manufacturer specification.\n\nLEAK DETECTION:\nElectronic leak detector: Sensor near all connections, hears an alarm tone when refrigerant detected.\nSoap solution: Brush on connections, refrigerant causes bubbling.\nUV dye: Add to system, use UV light to find leak.\nAfter finding and repairing leak: Evacuate, recharge.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nUsing a manifold gauge set, read the pressures on any available operating refrigeration or AC system.\nRecord high and low side pressures.\nResearch: What are the correct operating pressures for R134a at 25°C ambient?\nAre the pressures you measured within the correct range?'),

    (5, 'Refrigeration and AC Business', 15,
     'The refrigeration and AC trade is in high demand and commands excellent rates.\n\nTHE MARKET:\nEvery supermarket, restaurant, hotel and hospital needs commercial refrigeration.\nHomes and offices increasingly install AC as incomes rise.\nEquipment requires regular maintenance and occasional repair.\nThe market grows with urbanisation and rising temperatures.\n\nSERVICES AND PRICING:\nDomestic fridge diagnosis and minor repair: Le 30,000-80,000 labour.\nGas recharge (fridge): Le 40,000-80,000 plus refrigerant cost.\nSplit AC installation (1 unit): Le 150,000-300,000 labour.\nAC maintenance service: Le 50,000-80,000 per unit.\nAC gas recharge: Le 80,000-150,000 plus refrigerant.\nWalk-in cold room installation: Le 500,000+ labour.\n\nCERTIFICATIONS:\nSome countries require refrigerant handling certification.\nManufacturer training (Daikin, Mitsubishi, LG) improves your credibility.\nCertification opens access to warranty work from distributors.\n\nTOOLS INVESTMENT:\nManifold gauge set: Le 200,000-500,000.\nVacuum pump: Le 250,000-500,000.\nRefrigerant scale: Le 100,000-200,000.\nElectronic leak detector: Le 100,000-300,000.\nThese pay back quickly on the first few jobs.\n\nMAINTENANCE CONTRACTS:\nOffer quarterly or annual maintenance contracts to commercial clients.\nPredictable income. Priority call-out service.\nBuilds long-term relationships with hotels, restaurants, supermarkets.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nVisit a local supermarket, hotel or restaurant.\nAsk if you can inspect their refrigeration equipment.\nNote: What brands? How old? When was it last serviced?\nPrepare a written maintenance proposal for one establishment.\nThis is your first commercial prospecting exercise.'),
])

# ============================================================
# HAIR AND BEAUTY
# ============================================================
add_lessons('Hair and Beauty', [
    (1, 'Introduction to Hair and Beauty Services', 15,
     'Hair and beauty is one of the most consistent and resilient businesses in West Africa. People maintain their appearance regardless of economic conditions.\n\nWHY HAIR AND BEAUTY IS AN EXCELLENT TRADE:\nEvery person needs haircuts, styling or beauty treatments.\nWomen and men spend consistently on hair and grooming.\nServices cannot be imported — they must be delivered locally.\nLow startup costs. Work from home or a small salon.\nHigh skill premium: Excellent stylists charge significantly more.\n\nSERVICES OVERVIEW:\n\nWOMEN\'S HAIR SERVICES:\nBraiding (plaiting): Traditional African braiding styles.\nRelaxing: Chemical straightening of natural hair.\nWeaving and extensions: Adding hair pieces for length and volume.\nNatural hair care: Twist-outs, loc maintenance, natural styles.\nColouring: Adding colour to natural or relaxed hair.\nCutting and trimming.\n\nMEN\'S HAIR SERVICES:\nHaircutting: Fades, shapes, trims.\nShaving: Beard shaping and shaving.\nHair texturising.\n\nBEAUTY SERVICES:\nFacials: Cleansing, exfoliation, treatment.\nManicure and pedicure: Nail care and polish.\nMakeup: Everyday and special occasion.\nEyebrow threading and waxing.\nLash extensions.\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY IN THE SALON:\nUse clean, sanitised tools for every client.\nNeedles, razors and scissors that break skin must be single-use or sterilised.\nShampoo and styling tools washed and sanitised between clients.\nChemical services: Wear gloves. Follow manufacturer timing instructions exactly.\nOverprocessed hair (chemical burns, breakage) damages your reputation.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nIdentify five hair and beauty businesses in your community.\nObserve: What services do they offer? How are they priced?\nWhat is the quality level? What is busy and what is quiet?\nWhat gap in services could you fill?'),

    (2, 'Hair Care and Braiding Techniques', 25,
     'Braiding is the most universally practised hair service across West Africa. Excellence in braiding builds a loyal client base.\n\nHAIR ANATOMY:\nHair is made of keratin (protein).\nScalp health affects hair health: A healthy scalp grows healthy hair.\nHair types: Straight, wavy, curly, coily/kinky (most common in West Africa).\nNatural African hair requires moisture — it is prone to dryness and breakage if not properly conditioned.\n\nPREPARING HAIR FOR BRAIDING:\nWash hair thoroughly with shampoo.\nCondition: Apply conditioner, leave 5-10 minutes, rinse.\nDetangle gently with wide-tooth comb working from ends to roots.\nDry or blow dry if doing styles that require dry hair.\nApply leave-in conditioner or hair oil to moisturise.\n\nBRAIDING TECHNIQUES:\n\nCORNROWS:\nBraid flat against the scalp in rows.\nPart hair in straight lines from front to back (or in patterns for decorative styles).\nDivide section into three strands.\nCross strands alternately under the centre strand, picking up small sections from scalp with each cross.\nKeep tension even throughout — too tight causes headaches and traction alopecia.\n\nBOX BRAIDS:\nFreed braids hanging from scalp.\nPart hair into square sections.\nAttach extension hair and braid down to the end.\nSize varies: Micro (very thin), medium, jumbo.\n\nFEEDER BRAIDS:\nStart small at the root, gradually adding more extension hair.\nCreates a tapered, natural look at the scalp.\n\nTWIST STYLES:\nTwo-strand twists: Divide section into two strands. Twist each strand then twist them around each other.\nPassion twists, Senegalese twists, Marley twists: Variations using different extension types.\n\nTAKING DOWN BRAIDS:\nLoosen gradually. Never pull.\nApply oil or conditioner to ease removal.\nDo not pull out knots — cut extension hair if necessary.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPractice cornrows on a mannequin head or willing volunteer.\nAim for: Even sections, consistent tension, neat edges, straight rows.\nTime yourself. Professional speed comes with practice.'),

    (3, 'Chemical Services — Relaxing and Colouring', 25,
     'Chemical services command premium prices but require knowledge and care to avoid damaging clients\' hair.\n\nHAIR RELAXING:\nA chemical relaxer breaks down the protein bonds that give hair its curl pattern.\nResult: Straight or more manageable hair.\nRelaxer types:\nLye (sodium hydroxide): Stronger. Faster. More potential for scalp irritation.\nNo-lye (potassium hydroxide or guanidine): Gentler. Better for sensitive scalps.\n\nCONTRAINDICATIONS — Do NOT relax if:\nClient has an open scalp sore or scratch.\nClient relaxed within the last 6-8 weeks (overlap leads to breakage).\nHair is severely damaged or broken.\nClient is pregnant (precautionary).\n\nRELAXER APPLICATION:\nProtect scalp with base cream (petroleum jelly) applied carefully to scalp.\nWear gloves throughout.\nApply relaxer to new growth only (not previously relaxed hair).\nProcess for manufacturer\'s recommended time — never guess.\nRinse THOROUGHLY with warm water for at least 3-5 minutes.\nApply neutralising shampoo: Stops chemical action. Lather twice, leave 3 minutes each.\nFollow with deep conditioning treatment.\n\nHAIR COLOURING:\nTemporary colour: Rinses out after 1-2 shampoos.\nSemi-permanent: Lasts 4-6 weeks.\nPermanent colour: Requires developer. Lifts natural colour and deposits new colour.\nDo strand test first: Check colour result and check for breakage.\nDo patch test: Check for allergic reaction behind ear 48 hours before full application.\nNever colour recently relaxed hair — hair is already stressed.\n\nTREATING HAIR DAMAGE:\nProtein treatment: Strengthens damaged, brittle hair.\nDeep conditioning: Restores moisture to dry, porous hair.\nTrimming: Remove split ends that cause further breakage.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPractice applying hair colour on a mannequin head or hair piece.\nFollow manufacturer instructions exactly.\nCheck timing. Rinse thoroughly.\nEvaluate result: Is the colour even? Was there any damage?'),

    (4, 'Nail Care and Basic Beauty Services', 20,
     'Nail care and beauty services complement hair services and increase your earning per client.\n\nMANICURE PROCEDURE:\nSoak hands in warm soapy water (5-10 minutes).\nPush back cuticles gently with orange stick.\nTrim or file nails to desired length and shape.\nNail shapes: Square, oval, round, almond, stiletto.\nApply base coat. Allow to dry.\nApply 2 coats of chosen colour. Allow each coat to dry.\nApply top coat for shine and longevity.\nClean up edges with a thin brush dipped in nail polish remover.\n\nPEDICURE PROCEDURE:\nSoak feet in warm soapy water (10-15 minutes). Add foot soak product.\nScrub with pumice stone or foot file to remove hard skin.\nTrim toenails straight across (prevents ingrown nails).\nFile smooth. Push back cuticles.\nSeparate toes with toe separators.\nApply base coat, two colour coats, top coat.\nFinish with moisturising foot cream.\n\nSANITATION IN NAIL SERVICES:\nFile and buff tools: Single use per client, or sanitise in disinfectant.\nMetal tools: Wash, then sterilise in autoclave or UV steriliser.\nNever use the same nail file on two clients.\nSoaking bowls: Disinfect between clients.\n\nBASIC FACIAL:\nCleanse: Remove makeup and surface dirt.\nExfoliate: Remove dead skin cells (gently).\nTone: Restore pH balance.\nMask: Treat specific skin concerns.\nMoisturise: Apply appropriate moisturiser.\nSPF: Apply sunscreen as final step (important in West African sun).\n\nSKIN TYPES:\nNormal: Balanced. Not oily or dry.\nOily: Shiny, pores visible, prone to breakouts.\nDry: Tight feeling, may flake, prone to fine lines.\nCombination: Oily T-zone (forehead, nose, chin), normal or dry cheeks.\nSensitive: Reacts easily to products. Use fragrance-free, gentle products.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nGive a classmate or family member a basic manicure.\nFollow the complete procedure.\nAsk for feedback: How did it feel? How does it look?\nPractice until your technique is smooth and efficient.'),

    (5, 'Running a Salon Business', 15,
     'A well-run salon is a profitable, resilient business that serves the community every day.\n\nSETTING UP YOUR SALON:\nLocation: Residential areas where your clients live. Near schools, markets, churches.\nEquipment: Salon chair, mirror, shampoo basin (or portable alternative), hairdryer, styling tools.\nAmbiance: Clean, welcoming, organised. Music at appropriate volume. Magazines or phone chargers for waiting clients.\nSanitation visible: Clients should SEE you sanitising tools between clients. It builds trust.\n\nPRICING YOUR SERVICES:\nResearch local salon prices.\nKnow your costs: Products used per service, overhead allocation, your time.\nPrice to cover costs with minimum 40% profit margin.\nSpecialist services command premium: Colour, extensions, special occasion styling.\n\nAPPOINTMENT MANAGEMENT:\nTake bookings by WhatsApp.\nConfirm the day before.\nManage waiting time professionally — do not keep clients waiting without acknowledgement.\nOver time, build a loyal clientele with regular appointments.\n\nRECORD KEEPING:\nNote every client: Name, contact, services received, products used, any allergies or sensitivities.\nThis allows personalised service and follow-up.\n\nBUILDING CLIENTELE:\nEvery satisfied client is a marketing agent.\nSpecial occasion clients (weddings, graduations): Offer to do a trial run. Take photos.\nChildren\'s services: Build relationships with entire families.\nMen\'s cuts: Often overlooked by female stylists — a lucrative addition.\n\nCONTINUING EDUCATION:\nNew styles, techniques and products emerge constantly.\nFollow top stylists on social media for inspiration and technique.\nAttend workshops and training when possible.\nInvest in your skills — they pay back for years.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCreate your service menu with prices.\nCreate a simple booking system using WhatsApp.\nCalculate: If you do 5 services per day at an average of Le 30,000, what is your monthly income?\nWhat expenses must come out of that income?'),
])

