# REMAINING 8 COURSES — SHORTER BUT COMPLETE
# ============================================================
add_lessons('Car Repairs and Maintenance', [
    (1, 'Understanding the Modern Car', 25, 'The modern car is a complex machine. Understanding its systems is the foundation of effective repair.\n\nCAR SYSTEMS:\nEngine: Converts fuel to mechanical power. Petrol or diesel. 4-stroke cycle.\nCooling system: Water, coolant, radiator, water pump, thermostat. Prevents overheating.\nLubrication: Engine oil, oil pump, oil filter. Reduces friction.\nFuel system: Fuel tank, pump, filter, injectors (modern) or carburettor (older).\nIgnition: Spark plugs, coil, electronic control unit. Starts combustion.\nTransmission: Gearbox, clutch (manual) or torque converter (automatic), driveshaft.\nElectrical: Battery, alternator, fuses, sensors, ECU (Engine Control Unit).\nSteering: Rack and pinion, power steering pump or electric motor.\nBrakes: Disc and caliper (front), drum or disc (rear), brake fluid, ABS.\nSuspension: Springs, shock absorbers, control arms. Absorbs road surface impact.\n\nTHE ENGINE CONTROL UNIT (ECU):\nModern cars are computer-controlled.\nSensors monitor: Oxygen levels, air mass, throttle position, coolant temperature, knock.\nECU adjusts fuel injection and ignition timing in real-time for efficiency and power.\nFaults stored as Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTCs) readable with OBD-II scanner.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nWith an OBD-II scanner (increasingly affordable), read fault codes from any available modern car.\nRecord all codes and research what each means.\nThis exercise introduces you to modern vehicle diagnosis.'),
    (2, 'Engine Servicing and Maintenance', 25, 'Regular servicing prevents costly breakdowns and extends engine life.\n\nSERVICE SCHEDULE:\nEvery 5,000-10,000 km or 6 months (check manufacturer specification):\nEngine oil and filter change.\nAir filter inspection and replacement if dirty.\nFuel filter replacement (interval varies).\nSpark plug inspection and replacement (every 30,000-60,000 km on modern engines).\nCoolant level check. Coolant flush every 2 years.\nBrake fluid check and replacement every 2 years.\nAll fluid levels: Power steering, transmission, windscreen wash.\nTyre pressures and condition.\nBattery terminals clean and tight.\nEvery 40,000-100,000 km:\nTiming belt (check manufacturer interval — critical).\nBrake pads and discs inspection.\nTransmission oil change.\n\nOIL AND FILTER CHANGE:\nWarm engine 2-3 minutes. Drain plug underneath sump. Allow all oil to drain.\nChange oil filter (twist off by hand or with filter wrench).\nFit new filter. Replace drain plug. Fill with correct grade and quantity of oil.\nStart engine. Check for leaks. Check dipstick after 1 minute.\n\nCOOLANT:\nNever open radiator cap when engine is hot. Risk of scalding.\nCheck level in expansion tank when cold.\nMix coolant with water (50:50 for most climates).\nFlush every 2 years: Drain, flush with water, refill with fresh coolant.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nConduct a full service on a car.\nChange oil and filter. Check all fluid levels. Check air filter. Check tyre pressures.\nDocument everything: Fluids used, quantities, condition of filters, any concerns observed.'),
    (3, 'Brakes and Steering', 25, 'Safety-critical systems. Errors here can kill.\n\nDISC BRAKES:\nCaliper clamps pads onto spinning disc.\nCheck pad thickness through inspection hole in caliper: Minimum 3mm. Replace at 2mm.\nCheck disc: Measure thickness with vernier caliper. Compare to minimum specification (stamped on disc).\nScored discs (deep grooves): Replace or machine.\nReplacing brake pads:\nRemove wheel. Unscrew caliper. Push piston back with piston tool.\nInstall new pads. Refit caliper. Pump brake pedal to bring pads to disc.\nCheck brake fluid level in reservoir.\n\nDRUM BRAKES:\nShoes press outward onto drum.\nCheck shoe lining thickness: Minimum 3mm.\nCheck drum: Measure internal diameter. Must not exceed maximum specification.\nReplace springs and adjusters when replacing shoes.\nAdjust drum brake: Adjust star wheel until wheel drags slightly, then back off.\n\nBRAKE FLUID:\nHygroscopic (absorbs water). Must be replaced every 2 years.\nBoiling point drops as water content increases — causes brake fade on steep descents.\nBleeding brakes: Remove air and old fluid. Two-person job (one pumps, one opens bleeder).\n\nSTEERING:\nCheck: Steering wheel play (should be less than 10mm free movement).\nCheck: Power steering fluid level.\nUnusual noises: Worn ball joints, tie rod ends, worn CV joints.\nSteering pulls to one side: Check tyres first, then alignment.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nInspect front brake pads on any available car.\nMeasure pad thickness. Are they above the minimum? Would you recommend replacement?\nCheck brake fluid level and colour (fresh = clear/amber, old = dark brown).'),
    (4, 'Electrical Diagnosis', 20, 'Modern car electrical systems are complex but diagnosable with the right tools and approach.\n\nTHE DIAGNOSTIC APPROACH:\nNever guess on electrical faults. Test systematically.\n1. Retrieve fault codes with OBD-II scanner.\n2. Research what each code means and what it tests.\n3. Check the circuit involved: Power supply, ground connection, sensor signal.\n4. Test with multimeter. Compare to specification.\n5. Replace only what testing proves is faulty.\n\nCOMMON ELECTRICAL FAULTS:\n\nBATTERY NOT CHARGING:\nMeasure battery voltage at rest: Should be 12.4-12.7V.\nStart engine: Should read 13.8-14.4V if alternator charging.\nIf not charging: Check alternator drive belt, check alternator output.\n\nMISFIRE:\nOBD-II shows misfire code for specific cylinder (P0301 = cylinder 1 misfire).\nCheck: Spark plug for that cylinder. Ignition coil. Fuel injector. Compression.\nSwap coil with adjacent cylinder: If misfire moves, coil is faulty.\n\nOXYGEN SENSOR FAULT:\nAffects fuel economy and emissions.\nSensor monitors exhaust oxygen content and feeds ECU.\nTest with scanner: Should show fluctuating voltage (0.1V to 0.9V cycling).\nFlat line reading: Sensor faulty.\n\nWIRING AND CONNECTORS:\nCorrosion at connectors causes intermittent faults.\nClean with electrical contact cleaner.\nBroken wires inside insulation: Flex the wire while checking with multimeter for continuity.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nUsing an OBD-II scanner, retrieve fault codes from a car.\nResearch each code.\nFor one code, describe: What the code means, what system is affected, what tests you would perform to diagnose the root cause.'),
    (5, 'Running a Car Repair Business', 15, 'Technical skills plus business skills create a sustainable income from car repair.\n\nTHE MARKET:\nMore cars are on West African roads than ever before.\nMost are older vehicles requiring more maintenance.\nQuality mechanics with modern diagnostic skills are scarce and valuable.\nFlexi-service customers: Regular customers who trust you with every service.\n\nSETTING UP:\nTools are your biggest investment. Buy quality gradually.\nEssential first: Comprehensive socket set, spanners, jacks and axle stands, OBD-II scanner.\nAdd over time: Diagnostic equipment, air compressor, oil drainer.\n\nDIAGNOSIS FEE:\nCharge for diagnosis time. Professional mechanics charge for their knowledge.\nDeduct from repair cost if customer proceeds.\n\nBUILDING TRUST:\nShow clients the faulty part before replacing it.\nExplain in plain language what is wrong.\nCall to confirm additional work before doing it.\nReturn the car clean.\nDocument all work done and provide a simple job sheet.\n\nPRICING:\nResearch local market rates.\nDo not undercharge. Quality work commands quality prices.\nPackage deals: Service package combining oil change, filter, check for one price.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCreate your service menu with prices for your 10 most common repairs.\nCalculate: What is your target monthly income? How many jobs per week do you need to achieve it?\nWrite your unique selling point: Why should customers choose you over other mechanics?'),
])

add_lessons('Truck and Commercial Vehicle Maintenance', [
    (1, 'Introduction to Commercial Vehicles', 20, 'Trucks and commercial vehicles are the backbone of West African economies. Their maintenance keeps trade moving.\n\nTYPES OF COMMERCIAL VEHICLES:\nMini trucks and pickups: 1-3 tonne payload. Common for deliveries.\nMedium trucks: 5-15 tonne. Regional cargo transport.\nHeavy trucks (HGV): 20-40 tonne. Long-haul freight.\nTankers: Liquid cargo — fuel, water, palm oil.\nBuses and minibuses (Danfo, Trotro, Poda-poda): Passenger transport.\nConstruction vehicles: Tipper trucks, concrete mixers.\n\nDIFFERENCES FROM CAR MAINTENANCE:\nHeavier loads require stronger, more durable components.\nDiesel engines are standard (greater torque and economy for heavy loads).\nAir brakes rather than hydraulic brakes on larger trucks.\nLarger tyres with higher load ratings.\nMore frequent and more complex servicing requirements.\nFleet operation: Many trucks are part of a fleet — maintenance contracts possible.\n\nDIESEL ENGINE ADVANTAGES:\nHigher compression ratio: No spark plug. Air compressed until hot enough to ignite diesel.\nMore torque at lower RPM: Better for pulling heavy loads.\nBetter fuel economy at high load.\nLonger engine life with proper maintenance.\n\nKEY CHECKS BEFORE DRIVING:\nAll trucks should have a pre-trip inspection. A professional driver does this daily.\nOil level. Coolant level. Brake air pressure (should reach normal operating pressure before moving).\nTyres: Pressure and visible condition. Check all wheels including spare.\nLights: All lights functioning.\nMirrors: Positioned correctly.\nLoad: Secured. Weight within limits.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nConduct a pre-trip inspection on any available truck or large vehicle.\nUse the checklist above.\nDocument any deficiencies found.\nWhat would prevent you from driving this vehicle?'),
    (2, 'Diesel Engine Maintenance', 25, 'Diesel engines are workhorses that last hundreds of thousands of kilometres with proper maintenance.\n\nDIESEL ENGINE SERVICE INTERVALS:\nOil and filter change: Every 10,000-25,000 km (check manufacturer). More frequent under severe conditions.\nFuel filter change: Every 20,000-40,000 km. Critical — dirty fuel destroys injectors.\nAir filter: Every 20,000-40,000 km or when restriction indicator shows.\nCoolant flush: Every 2 years or 100,000 km.\nFan belt tension check: Every service.\nValve clearance check: Every 40,000-80,000 km.\n\nFUEL SYSTEM:\nDiesel injectors are precision components requiring clean fuel.\nWater contamination is the biggest enemy of diesel fuel systems.\nDrain water separator (fuel filter base) every week.\nUse quality fuel from reputable stations.\nInjector replacement is expensive — prevention is far cheaper.\n\nTURBOCHARGER MAINTENANCE:\nMost commercial diesel engines are turbocharged.\nOil is critical to turbo bearing life.\nAlways use correct oil viscosity.\nAllow engine to idle for 2 minutes before shutdown (hot turbo needs oil cooling).\nNever rev a cold engine hard immediately after starting.\nTurbo rebuild or replacement is expensive — proper oil management prevents premature failure.\n\nCOMMON DIESEL FAULTS:\nBlack smoke: Over-fuelling, worn injectors, blocked air filter.\nBlue smoke: Oil burning — worn piston rings or valve seals.\nWhite smoke (cold): Normal at cold start. Persistent: Head gasket, injector fault.\nHard starting: Weak glow plugs, low compression, poor fuel quality.\nExcessive fuel consumption: Injectors, worn engine, air filter, tyre pressures.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nService the fuel filter on any available diesel vehicle.\nDrain and inspect the water separator: Is there water present?\nCheck air filter restriction indicator if fitted.\nCheck and adjust fan belt tension.'),
    (3, 'Air Brake Systems', 25, 'Air brakes are safer for heavy vehicles than hydraulic brakes. Understanding them is essential for truck mechanics.\n\nWHY AIR BRAKES:\nLarger vehicles require more braking force than hydraulic systems can provide.\nAir brakes get stronger when you press harder — hydraulic brakes can fade under sustained use.\nAir leak is immediately apparent to the driver (pressure gauge drops) — unlike hydraulic leaks.\nAir-powered brakes automatically apply if air pressure is lost (fail-safe).\n\nHOW AIR BRAKES WORK:\nAir compressor (engine-driven) pumps air to storage tanks.\nNormal operating pressure: 690-760 kPa (100-110 psi).\nBrake pedal connects to brake valve which releases air to brake chambers.\nSlack adjuster converts air chamber push into brake shoe force.\nLow pressure warning buzzer: Below 414 kPa (60 psi). Stop immediately.\nParking brake: Spring-applied. Air holds it off. Loss of air = automatic brake application.\n\nDAILY AIR BRAKE CHECKS:\nAllow system to build to full pressure before moving.\nCheck for leaks: Listen with engine off. Pressure should not drop more than 14 kPa (2 psi) per minute.\nTest low pressure warning: Pump brakes with engine off until warning sounds.\nTest parking brake: Apply parking brake. Try to drive forward gently. Vehicle should not move.\n\nSLACK ADJUSTER:\nAutomatic slack adjusters should maintain correct brake adjustment automatically.\nManual check: With brakes released, push/pull on adjuster. Should not move more than 19mm.\nIf adjustment is out: Automatic adjuster may be faulty. Check and replace if needed.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nOn any available truck, check air brake system operation:\nBuild pressure. Listen for leaks. Test low pressure warning. Test parking brake.\nDocument your findings. Are there any concerns?'),
    (4, 'Tyres and Wheel End Maintenance', 20, 'Truck tyres carry enormous loads. Correct maintenance prevents accidents and saves significant money.\n\nTRUCK TYRE SPECIFICATIONS:\nLoad index: Maximum load each tyre can carry. Printed on sidewall.\nSpeed rating: Maximum speed. Most truck tyres rated 120 km/h.\nSize: e.g., 11R22.5 (width, construction type, rim diameter).\nSingle or dual tyres: Many trucks run dual rear tyres (two tyres per side).\n\nTYRE PRESSURE:\nCritically important for truck tyres — much more so than cars.\nUnder-inflation: Excessive heat, rapid wear, risk of blowout.\nOver-inflation: Reduced grip, uneven wear, harsh ride.\nCheck pressure cold (not after driving). Check every wheel.\nDual tyres: Check inner tyre — often ignored. If inner is flat, outer appears fine but is carrying double the load.\n\nTYRE WEAR PATTERNS:\nEdge wear: Under-inflation or poor alignment.\nCentre wear: Over-inflation.\nOne-sided wear: Incorrect camber or toe alignment.\nFeathering: Toe misalignment.\nDiagonal wear or cupping: Worn shock absorbers or wheel imbalance.\n\nWHEEL BEARING MAINTENANCE:\nWheel bearings carry the entire vehicle weight.\nInspect at every brake reline.\nCheck for: Excessive play (grab top and bottom of wheel, rock it), overheating after driving.\nRepack with grease at each inspection.\nWorn bearings cause wheel wobble, overheating and eventual wheel loss.\n\nBRAKE RELINE:\nTruck brake shoes typically last 100,000-200,000 km.\nAlways replace all shoes on an axle at the same time.\nAdjust brakes correctly after reline.\nRun-in period: Avoid heavy braking for first 200 km after reline.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCheck tyre pressures on all wheels of any available truck.\nInspect tread wear pattern on each tyre.\nWhat do the wear patterns tell you about alignment, inflation and suspension condition?'),
    (5, 'Fleet Maintenance and Business', 15, 'Fleet maintenance contracts are the most profitable segment of the commercial vehicle market.\n\nFLEET MAINTENANCE OPPORTUNITIES:\nTransport companies with 5+ trucks need a reliable mechanic.\nA service contract guarantees regular income and a stable client relationship.\nFleet operators value: Reliability, speed of repair, minimising downtime, honest reporting.\n\nFLEET MAINTENANCE CONTRACT:\nMonthly retainer: Fixed monthly fee covers routine services and inspections.\nCall-out rate: For breakdown repairs outside of routine service.\nParts supply: Fleet operators may supply parts; you supply labour.\nReporting: Regular written reports on fleet condition.\n\nMAINTENANCE SCHEDULING:\nGood fleet maintenance is planned, not reactive.\nService each vehicle at its interval regardless of whether symptoms are present.\nSchedule during vehicle\'s down time (night, slow periods).\nMaintain records: Service history, parts replaced, upcoming service dates.\n\nMINIMISING DOWNTIME:\nFleet operators lose money every day a truck is off the road.\nDiagnose quickly. Have common parts in stock.\nPrioritise: Get vehicle back on road, then complete secondary issues.\nCommunicate: Update fleet manager regularly on progress and timeline.\n\nBUILDING FLEET RELATIONSHIPS:\nApproach transport companies, logistics firms, construction companies.\nOffer a free fleet inspection as introduction.\nProvide a written report of findings — this demonstrates your expertise.\nStart with small jobs to build trust before seeking the full contract.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nIdentify three fleet operators in your area (transport companies, logistics firms, construction).\nPrepare a brief introduction to your services.\nOffer to conduct a free inspection of one vehicle as a demonstration.\nThis is your first fleet sales call.'),
])

add_lessons('Heavy Plant and Equipment Operation', [
    (1, 'Introduction to Heavy Plant', 20, 'Heavy plant operators are among the highest-paid skilled workers in West African construction.\n\nTYPES OF HEAVY PLANT:\nExcavator (digger): Digging, loading, demolition. Most versatile machine.\nBulldozer: Pushing material, land clearing, rough grading.\nGrader (motor grader): Fine grading, road smoothing, drainage shaping.\nLoader (front end loader): Loading materials into trucks.\nRoller (compactor): Compacting soil, gravel, tarmac.\nConcrete mixer truck: Mixing and delivering concrete.\nTipper trucks: Carrying and tipping bulk materials.\nCranes: Lifting heavy loads to height.\n\nSAFETY — THE MOST IMPORTANT LESSON:\nHeavy plant is involved in a significant proportion of construction fatalities.\nSlow down: Never rush. One mistake causes injuries you cannot undo.\nNever: Travel with raised attachments. Position them low for travel.\nNever: Operate without knowing your swing and travel clearances.\nAlways: Walk the work area before starting. Know where workers and services are.\nAlways: Use a banksman (ground guide) when working near people or structures.\nCheck all around: Especially behind, before reversing.\n\nPRE-OPERATIONAL INSPECTION:\nEvery operator must inspect the machine before starting work.\nEngine: Oil level, coolant level, fuel level.\nHydraulics: Fluid level, check for leaks under machine and around cylinder rods.\nTyres or tracks: Condition, inflation (tyres), tension (tracks).\nAttachments: Pins and clips secure.\nLights and horn: Working.\nSeat belt: Fitted and functional.\nFire extinguisher: Present and charged.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nConduct a pre-operational inspection on any available heavy plant.\nUse the checklist above.\nDocument any defects found.\nWould you operate this machine? If not, why not?'),
    (2, 'Excavator Operation', 30, 'The excavator is the most versatile and widely used piece of heavy plant on any construction site.\n\nEXCAVATOR CONTROLS:\nLeft joystick (SAE control pattern - most common):\nForward/back: Swing left/right.\nLeft/right: Boom down/up.\nRight joystick:\nForward/back: Arm curl in/out.\nLeft/right: Bucket curl in/out.\nFoot pedals: Travel forward and reverse.\nFoot control: Blade (on some machines).\n\nBASIC OPERATIONS:\n\nDIGGING:\nPosition machine with tracks perpendicular to work.\nLower boom. Extend arm. Curl bucket into ground.\nLift boom to raise full bucket.\nSwing to spoil heap or truck.\nOpen bucket to dump.\nReturn and repeat.\nKeep bucket teeth at correct angle of attack for efficient digging.\n\nLOADING TRUCKS:\nPosition truck alongside excavator (avoid swinging over cab).\nDump at rear of truck first, work forward.\nCommunicate with truck driver. Agree signals before starting.\nNever swing bucket over truck cab.\n\nBACKFILLING:\nPlace material in lifts (layers).\nCompact each lift before adding more (if specification requires).\nAvoid striking underground services.\n\nSAFETY AROUND EXCAVATORS:\nKill zone: 10m radius around operating excavator — no pedestrians without banksman control.\nExcavation edges: Soil can collapse. Keep away from excavation edges.\nOverhead lines: Know the position of all overhead electrical lines. Maintain safe clearance.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nIf access to a machine is possible: Under qualified supervision, operate basic excavator controls in a safe area.\nIf not: Find simulator software or videos and practice identifying correct control inputs for each operation.'),
    (3, 'Grader and Compaction Equipment', 25, 'Graders and compactors are essential for road construction and site preparation.\n\nMOTOR GRADER:\nUsed for: Road grading, drainage shaping, material spreading, snow clearing.\nBlade: The main working tool. Can be angled, tilted and raised/lowered.\n\nGRADER CONTROLS:\nArticulation: Bends the grader for tight manoeuvres and crowning.\nBlade lift: Raises and lowers both ends of blade independently.\nBlade circle rotation: Rotates blade left or right of centre.\nBlade angle: Angles blade forward or back.\n\nROAD GRADING:\nStart from edge of road, move material to centre.\nPassport approach: Multiple overlapping passes.\nAim for: Correct camber (slope away from centre for drainage), smooth surface, correct line.\nFinal pass: Light, no more material being moved. Just smoothing.\n\nVIBRATORY ROLLER:\nCompacts soil and gravel by combining weight and vibration.\nVibration: The drums vibrate rapidly, which increases compaction beyond weight alone.\nCompaction layers: Maximum 200-300mm per lift for effective compaction.\nTest: Drive over compacted material. If it sinks under the roller, add more passes.\nOver-compaction: Can damage gravel roads by breaking aggregate. Stop when surface stops deforming.\n\nSHEEPSFOOT ROLLER:\nDrum covered in protruding feet.\nBest for: Compacting clayey soils. Feet knead and compact the clay.\n\nCONTROL TESTING:\nProctor test: Laboratory test to determine optimum moisture content for compaction.\nDynamic Cone Penetrometer (DCP): Simple field test for compaction adequacy.\nOn large projects, an engineer may require compaction testing. Know what these tests mean.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nObserve a grader or roller in operation.\nNote: What passes are being made? What evidence is there of adequate compaction?\nDiscuss with the operator: What challenges are they facing with this material?'),
    (4, 'Plant Maintenance and Servicing', 20, 'Heavy plant represents enormous capital investment. Proper maintenance protects that investment.\n\nWHY MAINTENANCE IS CRITICAL:\nHeavy plant costs hundreds of thousands to millions of dollars.\nBreakdown on a construction site stops all work and incurs huge daily losses.\nProper maintenance prevents most breakdowns.\nA well-maintained machine sells for significantly more than a neglected one.\n\nSERVICE INTERVALS:\nFollow manufacturer\'s maintenance schedule. Hours-based, not kilometres.\nEvery 10 hours (daily):\nEngine oil level. Coolant level. Fuel level. Hydraulic fluid level.\nWalking inspection: Look for leaks, damage, loose items.\nCheck tracks (tension and condition for tracked machines).\nEvery 250 hours:\nEngine oil and filter change.\nFuel filter change.\nHydraulic return filter change.\nEvery 500 hours:\nHydraulic oil analysis. Drive final drives fluid change.\nEvery 1,000-2,000 hours:\nHydraulic oil change. Coolant change. Major inspection.\n\nHYDRAULIC SYSTEM CARE:\nHydraulic oil contamination is the major cause of hydraulic system failure.\nAlways use clean containers and funnels when adding hydraulic oil.\nFix all hydraulic leaks immediately — leaks allow contamination in.\nCheck cylinder rod seals: If weeping or leaking, replace before worse damage occurs.\n\nTRACK MAINTENANCE:\nTrack tension: Too tight causes premature wear. Too loose causes de-tracking.\nCheck and adjust every 50 hours or after working in sticky soil.\nTrack shoe condition: Replace worn shoes before metal-to-metal contact damages rollers.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPerform a 10-hour daily inspection on any available heavy plant.\nDocument all findings including fluid levels, condition of visible components, any leaks.\nWhat action does each finding require?'),
    (5, 'Career in Heavy Plant', 15, 'Heavy plant operators are in high demand across West Africa with construction booming.\n\nCAREER PATHWAYS:\nOperator: Operates one type of machine. Starting point.\nSenior operator: Proficient in multiple machines. Higher pay.\nSupervisor/foreman: Manages a team of operators and labourers.\nPlant manager: Responsible for a fleet of machines and their maintenance.\n\nSALARY RANGES:\nOperator salaries vary significantly by country, machine type and employer.\nHeavy plant operators typically earn 2-4 times the minimum wage.\nSenior operators on major projects (road construction, mining) earn very well.\nFreelance operators can earn more but bear their own costs and downtime risk.\n\nGETTING EXPERIENCE:\nMost operators start as helpers or labourers on construction sites.\nShow initiative: Observe operators, learn the machine, volunteer to assist.\nSome construction companies offer structured training for promising workers.\nTraining schools: Heavy plant training centres exist in major cities.\n\nCERTIFICATION:\nMany countries require formal certification to operate heavy plant.\nResearch certification requirements in your country before seeking work.\nCertification usually requires: Theory test, practical assessment on the machine type.\n\nSAFETY RECORD:\nConstruction companies check your safety record.\nA serious accident on your record makes future employment very difficult.\nSafety is not just ethics — it is career protection.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nResearch heavy plant training facilities in your country or region.\nWhat does operator certification require? What does it cost? How long does it take?\nIdentify two construction companies in your area that operate heavy plant.\nHow could you make contact to enquire about opportunities?'),
])

add_lessons('Livestock Farming and Animal Husbandry', [
    (1, 'Introduction to Small-Scale Livestock', 20, 'Livestock farming provides food, income and financial security for millions of West African families.\n\nLIVESTOCK TYPES FOR SMALL-SCALE FARMERS:\nPoultry (chickens, ducks, guinea fowl): Fastest return. Low capital requirement.\nGoats: Hardy, adaptable, year-round breeding. High demand for meat and sacrifice.\nPigs: Efficient feed conversion. Fast growth. High value per animal.\nSheep: Similar to goats. Popular for celebrations and sacrifice.\nCattle: Highest capital requirement. Highest value. Dairy potential.\n\nCHOOSING WHICH LIVESTOCK:\nYour capital: Poultry most affordable, cattle most expensive.\nYour land: Poultry need less space than larger animals.\nLocal market: What sells best in your area?\nYour knowledge: Start with what you or someone nearby already knows.\nYour goal: Quick return (poultry) vs long-term asset (cattle).\n\nFARMING SYSTEMS:\nScavenging (extensive): Animals roam freely and find their own food.\nLow cost. Low productivity. Disease risk.\nSemi-intensive: Confined at night, some supplementary feeding.\nBalance of cost and productivity.\nIntensive: Confined at all times. Controlled feeding.\nHighest productivity. Requires more management and investment.\n\nFEED:\nAnimals need: Energy (carbohydrates and fats), Protein, Minerals, Vitamins, Water.\nFeed is the biggest cost in intensive farming.\nFormulated feeds ensure balanced nutrition.\nLocalised feeding: Maize, sorghum, cassava, groundnut cake, fish meal.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nVisit a local livestock farmer.\nWhat species do they keep? What system? What are their biggest challenges?\nAsk about: Where they sell, what they feed, what diseases they encounter, what they earn.\nWrite a one-page summary of what you observed and learned.'),
    (2, 'Poultry Farming', 25, 'Poultry is the most accessible livestock enterprise — quick returns, manageable investment.\n\nTYPES OF POULTRY PRODUCTION:\nBroilers: Meat chickens. Sold at 6-8 weeks. Fast turnover.\nLayers: Eggs. Production starts at 18-20 weeks. Continuous income for 12-18 months.\nNative/local chickens: Slower growth but premium price for meat and eggs.\n\nBROILER PRODUCTION CYCLE:\nDay-old chicks sourced from hatchery.\nWeek 1-3: Brooding (need warmth — 32-35°C reducing to 24°C by week 3).\nWeek 4-6: Grow-out phase. Eat well, gain weight rapidly.\nWeek 6-8: Ready for market (approximately 2-2.5 kg liveweight).\n\nHOUSING:\nDry, well-ventilated, secure from predators.\nDeep litter (wood shavings): Changed between flocks.\nPoultry wire sides in West African climate: Essential for ventilation.\nDensity: 8-10 birds per square metre for broilers.\n\nFEED PROGRAMME:\nStarter (Day 1 to Day 14): High protein (22%). Small crumble size.\nGrower (Day 15 to Day 28): 20% protein.\nFinisher (Day 29 to market): 18% protein.\nFeed conversion ratio: Approximately 2kg feed per 1kg liveweight gain. Better FCR = more profit.\n\nVACCINATION PROGRAMME:\nNewcastle Disease: Major killer of poultry. Vaccinate at Day 7, Day 21, then monthly.\nGumboro (IBD): Vaccinate at Day 10 and Day 21.\nMissed vaccination: One outbreak can destroy an entire flock.\n\nCOMMON DISEASES:\nNewcastle Disease: Respiratory, nervous signs, high mortality.\nGumboro: Depression, ruffled feathers, sudden deaths in 3-6 week birds.\nCoccidiosis: Bloody diarrhea, poor growth. Treat with coccidiostats in water.\nMycoplasma: Respiratory, rattling sounds, poor growth.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCalculate the economics of a 100-bird broiler batch:\nCost of chicks, feed for 7 weeks, medication and vaccines, housing costs.\nExpected market weight and price.\nIs this venture profitable? What is the profit per batch?'),
    (3, 'Goat and Small Ruminant Management', 20, 'Goats are the ideal livestock for smallholder farmers: Hardy, adaptable and in constant demand.\n\nGOAT BREEDS IN WEST AFRICA:\nWest African Dwarf (WAD): Most common. Small but disease-resistant, especially trypanosomiasis.\nSahel goat: Larger. Found in drier northern regions.\nCrossbreeds: WAD crossed with larger breeds for better growth.\n\nFEEDING GOATS:\nGoats are browsers (prefer leaves, shrubs, herbs) rather than grazers (grass).\nThey select quality feed — they will not eat dirty or contaminated feed.\nSupplement with: Maize bran, groundnut cake, mineral lick.\nWater: Clean water always available. Often forgotten but critical.\nNever: Feed mouldy or spoiled feed.\n\nHOUSING:\nElevated slatted floors are ideal: Droppings fall through, goats stay dry and clean.\nHoused at night for protection from predators.\nClean and dry: Damp conditions cause foot rot and respiratory disease.\n\nREPRODUCTION:\nDoe (female) reaches puberty at 6-10 months.\nGestation: 5 months (150 days).\nKidding (birth): Usually twins. Attend kidding to assist if needed.\nMilk kids adequately in first days — colostrum is critical for immunity.\nMate does at 12-18 months for first breeding.\n\nCOMMON DISEASES:\nSore mouth (orf): Viral. Scabby sores around mouth.\nPneumonia: Respiratory infection. Coughing, runny nose, fever. Treat with antibiotics.\nFoot rot: Lameness. Caused by wet, dirty conditions. Treat with footbath and antibiotics.\nInternal parasites: Worms are the biggest challenge in goat farming. Regular deworming essential.\nDeworming resistance: Rotate anthelmintics. Do not overdose or underdose.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nDesign a simple goat house for 10 does and 1 buck.\nDrawing with dimensions, materials needed, estimated cost.\nList the feeds available in your area suitable for goats.\nCalculate cost of keeping 10 goats for one month.'),
    (4, 'Animal Health and Disease Prevention', 20, 'Prevention is far cheaper than treatment. Healthy animals are productive animals.\n\nPRINCIPLES OF DISEASE PREVENTION:\nBiosecurity: Keep your farm clean and prevent disease entering.\nVaccination: Protect against specific diseases before they arrive.\nNutrition: Well-nourished animals resist disease better.\nHousing: Clean, dry, well-ventilated housing prevents many diseases.\nSurveillance: Know your animals. Spot problems early.\n\nBIOSECURITY MEASURES:\nNew animals: Quarantine for 2-3 weeks before introducing to existing herd.\nVisitors: Limit access. Disinfect footwear.\nVehicles: Disinfect tyres that enter the farm.\nDead animals: Dispose by burning or deep burial immediately. Never leave near live animals.\nFeed storage: Covered and rodent-proof. Contaminated feed spreads disease.\n\nRECOGNISING SICK ANIMALS:\nBehaviour changes first: Dull, listless, standing apart from group.\nOff feed: Not eating or drinking normally.\nPhysical signs: Diarrhea, discharge from eyes or nose, coughing, skin lesions, lameness, bloat.\nWeight loss: A healthy animal maintains condition. Progressive thinness indicates a problem.\n\nVETERINARY DRUGS:\nAntibiotics: Treat bacterial infections. Use correct dose for correct number of days. Resistance from misuse is a serious problem.\nAnthelmintics (dewormers): Kill internal parasites. Rotate between classes to prevent resistance.\nVitamins and minerals: Injectable or in-feed supplements for deficiency conditions.\nNever use human medicines in animals without veterinary advice.\n\nRECORD KEEPING:\nDate and identify every treatment given.\nThis helps identify: Which animals are repeatedly sick (cull or investigate), which diseases are emerging, effectiveness of treatments.\nRequired for: Export markets, disease tracing, government inspection.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCreate a health calendar for a small poultry or goat enterprise.\nList: All vaccinations (what, when, how given), deworming schedule, housing cleaning schedule, routine inspections.\nResearch: What vaccinations are available in your area for your chosen species?'),
    (5, 'Livestock Business and Marketing', 15, 'The final goal of livestock farming is profitable sale. Marketing strategy determines your income.\n\nUNDERSTANDING YOUR MARKET:\nLive animal market: Most livestock in West Africa sold live at markets.\nMeat processors: Butchers, slaughterhouses. May offer better price for quality animals.\nDirect to consumer: Premium price but requires access to buyers.\nSupermarkets and hotels: Seek consistent quality supply. Possible premium market.\n\nSEASONAL PRICE PATTERNS:\nPrices peak before major festivals and religious celebrations.\nEid al-Adha: Massive demand for rams and goats. Prices triple or more.\nChristmas and New Year: High demand for poultry and pigs.\nPlan production to have animals ready for peak demand periods.\n\nANIMAL CONDITION AFFECTS PRICE:\nFat, healthy animals with good condition score sell for more.\nThin animals: Buyers discount heavily. Ensure animals are well-fed before sale.\nPresentation: Clean animals at market look better and attract buyers.\n\nPRICING YOUR ANIMALS:\nKnow the current market price for your species and weight.\nCost + profit = minimum acceptable price.\nDo not sell below cost. Better to hold animals if price is poor.\nBuild relationships with regular buyers who pay fair prices.\n\nGROWING YOUR ENTERPRISE:\nStart small: Build experience with 50-100 birds or 5-10 goats.\nRecord everything: Costs, income, performance. Identify what works.\nExpand gradually: Only grow when you are consistently profitable.\nDiversify: Multiple species reduce risk.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCalculate the profit per animal for your planned enterprise.\nResearch current market prices in your area.\nCalculate: How many animals must you sell per month to achieve your income target?\nWhat is your plan to reach that volume?'),
])

add_lessons('Crop Farming and Agribusiness', [
    (1, 'Soil and Crop Fundamentals', 20, 'Understanding soil is understanding farming. Good soil management is the foundation of profitable crop production.\n\nWHY SOIL MATTERS:\nSoil provides: Water, nutrients, physical support and biological activity for plants.\nDegraded soil: Low yields, high fertiliser dependency, erosion.\nHealthy soil: High yields, lower input costs, sustainable production.\n\nSOIL TYPES:\nSandy soil: Light, drains fast, warms quickly. Poor water and nutrient retention.\nClay soil: Heavy, drains slowly. Good nutrient retention but waterlogged easily.\nLoam: Mix of sand, silt and clay. Ideal for most crops. Good drainage and nutrient retention.\nHumus: Decomposed organic matter. Improves all soil types.\n\nSEASONS AND RAINFALL:\nMost West African farmers depend on rainwater.\nRainy season: Planting and main growing period.\nDry season: Harvest and land preparation.\nDual-season areas: Two planting seasons per year — early and late rains.\nIrrigation: Allows dry-season farming. High potential income from vegetables.\n\nCROP SELECTION:\nChoose crops suited to your local climate and soil.\nConsider market demand — can you sell what you grow?\nConsider risk: Diverse crops reduce impact of one crop failure.\nCash crops: Grown primarily for sale (cocoa, groundnuts, palm oil, vegetables).\nFood crops: For household consumption with surplus for sale (cassava, yam, maize, rice).\n\nLAND PREPARATION:\nClear vegetation. Burn or compost residue.\nLoosen soil to required depth (15-25cm for most annual crops).\nForm beds or ridges appropriate to the crop and drainage needs.\nAdd organic matter (compost, manure) and fertiliser before planting.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nExamine soil from three different locations.\nDescribe the texture (rub between fingers), colour, smell.\nPerform the jar test: Add soil to water in a jar, shake, leave overnight. Sand settles first, then silt, then clay — shows soil composition.\nWhat improvements would each soil type need for good crop production?'),
    (2, 'Planting and Crop Management', 25, 'Correct planting and management throughout the growing season determines your yield.\n\nSEED SELECTION:\nUse certified seed where possible: Higher germination rate, disease resistance, known performance.\nSave seed from open-pollinated varieties: Select from best plants. Not from hybrids.\nSeed treatment: Fungicide and insecticide seed dressing reduces soil pest problems.\nSoaking seeds: 12-24 hours before planting speeds germination for some crops.\n\nPLANTING DENSITY:\nCorrect plant spacing maximises yield.\nToo dense: Competition for light, water, nutrients. Small plants, poor yield.\nToo sparse: Wasted land and resources. Low total yield.\nExamples: Maize 75cm x 25cm. Tomato 60cm x 60cm. Pepper 60cm x 45cm.\n\nGERMINATION AND EARLY GROWTH:\nKeep soil moist but not waterlogged during germination.\nProtect seedlings from birds, insects and strong sun.\nThin to correct density if sown densely.\nGap fill: Replant gaps where seeds failed to germinate.\n\nFERTILISATION:\nBasal fertiliser: Applied at or before planting. Usually NPK compound fertiliser.\nTop dressing: Applied during growth. Usually nitrogen (urea or CAN) to promote leafy growth.\nFoliar feeding: Sprayed on leaves. Fast uptake for deficiency correction.\nOrganic alternatives: Compost, animal manure, green manure. Slower release but improves soil structure.\n\nWATER MANAGEMENT:\nCrops need adequate water throughout the growing period.\nDrought stress at critical periods (flowering, grain filling) severely reduces yield.\nIrrigation options: Gravity-fed systems, pump irrigation, drip irrigation.\nOver-watering: Causes waterlogging, root rot, promotes fungal diseases.\n\nWEED CONTROL:\nWeeds compete for water, nutrients and light.\nCritical weed-free period: First 4-6 weeks after planting. Miss this and yield is severely reduced.\nMethods: Hand weeding, hoe, herbicides, mulch.\nHerbicides: Use correct herbicide for your crop. Pre-emergence vs post-emergence. Follow label.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPlant a test plot with any available crop.\nApply correct spacing. Record planting date.\nMonitor weekly: Germination percentage, crop growth, pest or disease signs.\nRecord any interventions: Weeding, fertiliser, irrigation, pest control.'),
    (3, 'Pest and Disease Management', 20, 'Pests and diseases can destroy crops if not managed. Prevention and early intervention are key.\n\nINTEGRATED PEST MANAGEMENT (IPM):\nIPM uses multiple methods to manage pests sustainably.\nMonitoring: Regularly inspect crops. Know what is normal. Spot problems early.\nPrevention: Cultural practices that reduce pest and disease risk.\nBiological: Natural enemies, beneficial insects.\nChemical: Pesticides as last resort.\nGoal: Acceptable yield at minimum cost and environmental impact.\n\nCOMPON WEST AFRICAN CROP PESTS:\nFallarmyworm: Destructive caterpillar affecting maize, sorghum, millet. Feeds inside the whorl.\nAphids: Suck plant sap. Spread viruses. Honeydew promotes sooty mould.\nWhitefly: Suck sap, spread viruses particularly in tomato and other vegetables.\nStemborers: Bore into maize and sorghum stems. Kills plants or causes lodging.\nLocust: Periodic outbreaks. Watch for swarm warnings.\n\nDISEASE MANAGEMENT:\nFungal diseases: Encouraged by wet conditions, dense planting, susceptible varieties.\nMaize grey leaf spot, tomato blight, yam anthracnose, cocoa black pod.\nBacterial diseases: Cassava bacterial blight, banana Xanthomonas wilt.\nViral diseases: Spread by insects (aphids, whitefly). Control the vector to control the virus.\n\nPREVENTION:\nResistant varieties: Most effective and cheapest option.\nCrop rotation: Break pest and disease cycles. Do not plant same crop in same field consecutively.\nPlant spacing: Good airflow reduces fungal disease.\nSanitation: Remove and destroy infected plant material. Do not compost diseased plants.\nSeed health: Use disease-free, certified seed.\n\nPESTICIDE USE:\nAlways read and follow label instructions.\nWear protective clothing: Gloves, long sleeves, eye protection, boots.\nMix and apply correctly: Under-dosing builds resistance, over-dosing wastes money and harms environment.\nOther people: Never spray near water sources, beehives, or food crops close to harvest.\nStorage: Keep locked away from children. Original containers only.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nInspect any growing crop for pests and diseases.\nIdentify any pests or disease symptoms present.\nFor each problem found: What is it? How severe? What management is appropriate?'),
    (4, 'Harvest, Post-Harvest and Market', 20, 'Hard work in the field is wasted if harvest and post-harvest are poorly managed.\n\nHARVEST TIMING:\nHarvest at correct maturity — too early or too late reduces quality and storability.\nMaize: Grain maize at physiological maturity (husk dry, black layer at base of kernel).\nTomato: Red but still firm for market. If overripe, damaged in transport.\nYam: When leaves yellow and die back.\nGroundnut: When pods turn dark inside when opened.\n\nHARVEST METHODS:\nHand harvesting: Most common in West Africa. Labour intensive but gentle on produce.\nCutting tools: Machetes, knives. Keep sharp and clean.\nBundle, carry or crate: Avoid dropping or rough handling. Bruising causes rot.\n\nPOST-HARVEST LOSSES:\nPost-harvest losses in West Africa: 30-50% of produce. This is income thrown away.\nCauses: Poor storage, insect and rodent damage, fungal rot, mechanical damage.\nImpact: Farmers receive less income. Consumers face higher prices.\n\nSTORAGE:\nGrain: Dry to below 13% moisture content before storage. Store in sealed bags or metal silos.\nVegetables and fruit: Cool storage reduces spoilage. Difficult without electricity.\nYam and cassava: Traditional root cellars or properly ventilated stores.\nSmoked or dried fish: Preserves protein for storage and trade.\n\nADDING VALUE BEFORE SALE:\nGrading: Sort produce by size and quality. Premium buyers pay more for graded produce.\nCleaning and packaging: Clean, attractively presented produce sells better and for more.\nProcessing: Convert perishable produce into storable processed product.\n\nMARKETING:\nDo not sell only at harvest when prices are lowest.\nGroup marketing: Join farmer groups to sell collectively and access better prices.\nForward contracts: Agree sale price before harvest. Reduces price risk.\nValue chain: Know your value chain. Where is the profit in your crop? Can you capture more of it?\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nFor your most important crop:\nCalculate production cost per kg.\nResearch current market price per kg.\nCalculate profit per kg and profit per hectare.\nIs this profitable? What would you need to change to improve profitability?'),
    (5, 'Agribusiness — Farming as a Business', 15, 'The most successful farmers think and operate as businesspeople, not just farmers.\n\nTHE FARMING BUSINESS MINDSET:\nTraditional farmer: Plants what the family has always planted. Sells what is left after family consumption. Accepts whatever price the market offers.\nAgripreneur: Researches market demand before planting. Produces for sale with surplus for family. Negotiates price and adds value.\n\nFARM BUSINESS PLANNING:\nWhat to produce: Based on market research and your resources.\nHow much: Based on land, capital and market size.\nFor whom: Know your buyer before you plant.\nAt what price: Know your costs and required margin.\nHow to produce: Inputs, labour, management practices.\n\nFINANCIAL MANAGEMENT FOR FARMERS:\nTrack all costs: Land preparation, seeds, fertiliser, pesticides, labour, harvest, storage, transport.\nCalculate true cost per kg, per bag or per hectare.\nCompare to market price: Is this profitable?\nSeparate farm money from household money.\nSave for next season: Do not spend all harvest income.\n\nACCESS TO FINANCE:\nAgricultural development banks: Seasonal loans for inputs.\nMicrofinance institutions: Small loans for smallholders.\nSavings groups (susu/esusu): Community savings for shared investment.\nInput credit: Some input suppliers offer credit against harvest payment.\nCollateral: Land, equipment, expected harvest.\n\nFARMER ORGANISATIONS:\nCooperatives and farmer groups provide:\nCollective bargaining power for better input prices.\nGroup marketing for better output prices.\nAccess to training and government programmes.\nShared equipment ownership.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nChoose one crop and write a simple farm business plan:\nArea to plant. Inputs needed and cost. Labour requirements and cost.\nExpected yield. Expected selling price. Projected profit.\nSources of capital: What do you have? What do you need to borrow?\nThis is your farming business plan.'),
])

add_lessons('Photography and Videography', [
    (1, 'Camera Fundamentals', 20, 'Understanding your camera gives you creative and technical control over your images.\n\nCAMERA TYPES:\nSmartphone camera: Most people\'s starting point. Modern smartphones produce excellent images.\nPoint-and-shoot: Simple, automatic, compact. Good for casual photography.\nDSLR (Digital Single Lens Reflex): Professional quality. Interchangeable lenses. Full manual control.\nMirrorless: Modern alternative to DSLR. Same quality, smaller body.\nFor business photography in West Africa, a good smartphone or entry-level DSLR is sufficient to start.\n\nEXPOSURE TRIANGLE:\nThe three settings that control how much light reaches the sensor:\n\nISO: Sensitivity to light. Low ISO (100-400): Less sensitive, less grain, best quality. High ISO (800+): More sensitive, more grain. Use when light is insufficient.\n\nShutter Speed: How long the sensor is exposed to light. Fast (1/500s+): Freezes motion. Slow (1/30s or less): Blurs motion, needs tripod.\n\nAperture: Size of lens opening. f/1.8 (wide): Lots of light, shallow depth of field (background blurred). f/11 (narrow): Less light, everything sharp, landscape photography.\n\nWHITE BALANCE:\nDifferent light sources have different colour temperatures.\nAuto white balance (AWB): Works well in most situations.\nIncandescent: Warm orange light indoors.\nDaylight: For outdoor photography.\nCloudly: Adds warmth for overcast days.\n\nSHOOTING MODES:\nAuto: Camera decides everything. Good for learning.\nAperture priority (Av): You set aperture, camera sets shutter. Good for portraits.\nShutter priority (Tv): You set shutter, camera sets aperture. Good for action.\nManual (M): You control everything. Full creative control.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nUsing any camera or smartphone, photograph the same subject in:\nBright sunlight, shade, indoors.\nCompare the results. What changed? How did you compensate?\nTake 20 photos of one subject from different angles and distances.'),
    (2, 'Composition and Lighting', 25, 'Good composition and lighting separate professional photographers from amateurs.\n\nCOMPOSITION RULES:\n\nRULE OF THIRDS:\nDivide your frame into a 3x3 grid.\nPlace your subject at an intersection of grid lines, not the centre.\nMost cameras have a grid overlay option in settings.\nCreates visual interest and balance.\n\nLEADING LINES:\nLines that lead the viewer\'s eye into or through the image.\nRoads, paths, fences, rivers, shadows.\nPowerful tool for creating depth and movement in images.\n\nFRAMING:\nUse elements in the scene to frame your subject.\nDoorways, windows, trees, arches.\nAdds depth and context.\n\nSIMPLIFY:\nStrong images usually have one clear subject.\nRemove distracting background elements.\nChange angle to remove unwanted elements from frame.\nMove the camera until background is clean.\n\nLIGHTING:\n\nNATURAL LIGHT:\nThe golden hour: First hour after sunrise and last hour before sunset.\nSoft, warm, directional light. Most flattering for portraits and landscapes.\nHarsh midday sun: Creates unflattering shadows under eyes and noses. Avoid for portraits.\nOvercast light: Soft and even. Excellent for portraits and detail shots.\nIndoor natural light: Position subject near a window (not in direct sun).\n\nARTIFICIAL LIGHT:\nRing light: Creates even light, popular for portraits and video.\nSoftbox: Large soft light source. Professional studio quality.\nReflector: Bounces light into shadows. Affordable and effective.\nAvoid: Harsh on-camera flash directly at the subject.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nShoot one portrait in: Direct harsh sunlight, open shade, near a window, during golden hour.\nCompare the lighting quality and character of each.\nWhich do you prefer? Why? This is the beginning of developing your photographic eye.'),
    (3, 'Event and Portrait Photography', 25, 'Events and portraits are the bread and butter of professional photography in West Africa.\n\nEVENT PHOTOGRAPHY:\nCommon events: Weddings, naming ceremonies, graduations, birthday parties, funerals, festivals.\n\nPRE-EVENT PLANNING:\nMeet client before the event: Understand what moments are most important.\nKey shots list: Bride and groom, family groups, cutting the cake, key moments.\nArrive early: Photograph preparations, venue, detail shots.\nCharge batteries, format memory cards, bring spare cards.\n\nSHOOTING AT EVENTS:\nCapture decisive moments: The laugh, the tear, the first kiss, the prayer.\nShoot in burst mode for key moments — select the best frame later.\nCapture wide establishing shots, medium group shots and tight detail shots.\nMove quietly and unobtrusively — be a witness not a distraction.\nNatural light when possible. Flash when necessary — bounce off ceiling where possible.\n\nPORTRAIT PHOTOGRAPHY:\nBest lens: 50mm or 85mm equivalent for flattering perspective.\nDepth of field: Wide aperture (f/1.8-f/2.8) for blurred background (bokeh).\nEye focus: Always focus on the nearest eye. Soft eyes ruin a portrait.\nDirection: Ask subject to look slightly left or right of camera for natural look.\nExpression: Talk to your subject, make them comfortable. Natural expression beats forced smile.\nBackground: Clean, simple, not distracting.\n\nCHILDREN\'S PHOTOGRAPHY:\nGet down to their level — shoot at child\'s eye height.\nBe patient — children move unpredictably.\nCapture natural moments of play rather than posed expressions.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPhotograph a local event (with permission).\nCapture: Wide shot of venue, group shot, detail shot, candid moment, portrait of key person.\nEdit your best five images.\nPresent as a mini portfolio.'),
    (4, 'Video Production Basics', 25, 'Video content is increasingly in demand. Social media, events and commercial clients all need video.\n\nVIDEO BASICS:\nFrame rate: 24fps for cinematic feel. 25fps for TV (PAL standard). 60fps for smooth motion.\nResolution: 1080p HD is the minimum acceptable standard. 4K if your equipment supports it.\nStabilisation: Shaky video looks amateur. Use: Tripod, gimbal, image stabilisation setting in camera.\n\nSHOTS FOR VIDEO:\nWide shot: Establishes location and context.\nMedium shot: Torso and head. Conversation, interviews.\nClose-up: Face, hands, detail. Emotion and focus.\nExtreme close-up: Eyes, product detail. Intense focus.\nCover shots: B-roll footage to cut away to while narration continues.\n\nINTERVIEWS:\nFrame subject slightly off-centre. They look toward camera slightly.\nClean background. No distracting elements.\nRecord audio separately if possible (lapel microphone).\nLighting: Facing toward natural light or placed light. No harsh shadows on face.\nAsk open questions: Not yes/no. Tell me about your experience.\n\nSTORYTELLING:\nEvery video needs a beginning (establish), middle (develop), end (conclude).\nB-roll tells the story visually while audio carries the narrative.\nKeep attention: Change shots every 3-7 seconds.\nPace: Events are fast-paced. Documentaries are slower.\n\nSIMPLE EDITING:\nFree software: DaVinci Resolve (professional but free). CapCut (mobile, very easy).\nCut out mistakes and long pauses.\nOrder shots for narrative flow.\nAdd titles, music, transitions.\nColour correction: Ensure consistent look across clips.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nFilm a 2-minute video on any subject.\nInclude: Wide shot, medium shot, close-up, interview or narration.\nEdit into a coherent short video.\nShare for feedback.'),
    (5, 'Building a Photography Business', 15, 'Photography can generate excellent income with manageable startup costs.\n\nSERVICES TO OFFER:\nEvent photography: Weddings, naming ceremonies, graduations, parties.\nPortrait photography: Individuals, families, professional headshots.\nProduct photography: For businesses selling on WhatsApp or social media.\nCommercial photography: Hotels, restaurants, businesses for marketing.\nVideography: Event coverage, promotional videos, social media content.\n\nPRICING:\nWedding photography: Half day Le 500,000 to full day Le 1,500,000+ depending on your experience.\nPortrait session: Le 50,000-200,000 for a 1-2 hour session plus edited images.\nProduct photos: Le 20,000-50,000 per product or package deals.\nAlways include: Your time, editing time, the delivered images, travel if applicable.\n\nDELIVERING IMAGES:\nEdited images via Google Drive, WeTransfer or WhatsApp.\nProper editing: Colour correction, exposure, crop. Consistent style.\nNumber of images: Typically 50-100 edited images for a standard event.\nTurnaround: Promise a realistic time. Meet it every time.\n\nBUILDING YOUR PORTFOLIO:\nStart by photographing friends, family, free events.\nBuild 20-30 strong images before charging.\nPortfolio should show variety: Events, portraits, different lighting.\nPost consistently on Instagram and WhatsApp. Before-and-afters. Behind the scenes.\n\nEQUIPMENT INVESTMENT:\nStart with: Best smartphone you can afford, a tripod, a reflector.\nSave for: Entry-level DSLR or mirrorless camera, 50mm lens.\nAdd later: External flash, additional lenses, lights for studio work.\nDo not wait for perfect equipment — start with what you have.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCreate your photography business on WhatsApp Business.\nAdd your best 10 photos as your catalogue.\nWrite your service menu with prices.\nShare your number with five people in your community who could need photography services.'),
])

add_lessons('Security Services and Guard Training', [
    (1, 'Introduction to Security Work', 15, 'Security is a growing profession across West Africa. A professional security officer protects lives and property.\n\nWHAT SECURITY OFFICERS DO:\nAccess control: Controlling who enters and exits premises.\nPatrol: Regular inspection of the area to deter and detect threats.\nSurveillance: Monitoring CCTV and observing for suspicious activity.\nEmergency response: First responder to incidents on site.\nCustomer service: First point of contact for visitors and staff.\nReport writing: Documenting incidents and observations.\n\nTYPES OF SECURITY DEPLOYMENT:\nManned guarding: Physical officer at post or on patrol.\nMobile patrol: Officers visiting multiple sites on a rotation.\nClose protection: Protecting an individual (bodyguard).\nEvent security: Crowd management and access control at events.\nCCTV operator: Monitoring camera systems.\nCash-in-transit: Protecting movement of money.\n\nPROFESSIONAL STANDARDS:\nA professional security officer is NOT a soldier or aggressive enforcer.\nPhysical force is used only as a last resort and within the law.\nThe role is primarily: Observation, communication and deterrence.\nProfessional appearance: Clean uniform, maintained equipment, proper bearing.\nConduct: Firm but courteous. Respectful of all people until they give reason otherwise.\n\nLEGAL FRAMEWORK:\nSecurity officers have the same powers as ordinary citizens unless specifically licensed.\nArrest: Citizens arrest is possible but risky. Contact police as first choice.\nSearch: Cannot search without consent unless specifically authorised.\nForce: Can use reasonable force to protect themselves or prevent serious crime.\nKnow your country\'s specific laws on private security.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nResearch the security licensing requirements in your country.\nIs there a mandatory licence or certification? Who issues it?\nWhat training is required?\nIdentify two reputable security companies in your area.'),
    (2, 'Access Control and Patrol Techniques', 20, 'Access control and patrol are the core operational skills of security work.\n\nACCESS CONTROL:\nObjective: Ensure only authorised people enter the premises.\nStandard procedure:\nCheck identification of every person seeking entry.\nConfirm authorisation: Call the host, check visitor list, verify access pass.\nLog entry: Name, time, vehicle registration if applicable, purpose of visit.\nIssue visitor pass or badge.\nEscort if required.\nLog exit: Time of departure. Retrieve visitor pass.\n\nACCESS CONTROL SYSTEMS:\nManual: Officer controls physical barrier (boom, gate, door).\nElectronic: Key card, fingerprint, PIN entry. Officer monitors and manages exceptions.\nVehicle access: Check driver, vehicle and cargo if authorised to do so.\n\nCHECKPOINT COMMUNICATION:\nMaintain radio contact with main control and other posts.\nReport all significant events: Unusual visitors, incidents, technical faults.\nLog all communications.\n\nPATROL TECHNIQUES:\nPurpose: Detect threats, reassure legitimate occupants, respond to incidents.\nRandom: Vary patrol routes and timing. Predictable patrols are easily avoided by criminals.\nObservation: Use senses — look for signs of intrusion, smell of smoke or gas, sounds of disturbance.\nCheck points: Physically check all doors, windows, gates are locked and secure.\nDocument: Note condition of all areas. Report anything unusual.\n\nSIGNALS AND CODES:\nLearn your company\'s radio codes.\nNever discuss sensitive security information on open radio.\nDistress signal: Know the procedure if an officer is in danger.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPractice an access control scenario: Role-play checking in an unknown visitor.\nRequire: Identification, confirm with host, log entry, issue badge.\nPractice a patrol: Walk a known route, checking doors and observing for anything unusual.\nWrite an entry in a security log for a routine patrol.'),
    (3, 'Emergency Response and Incident Management', 20, 'Security officers are usually first on scene when emergencies occur. Preparation saves lives.\n\nEMERGENCY TYPES:\nFire: Most common emergency. Clear and dangerous.\nMedical emergency: Collapse, heart attack, injury.\nSecurity breach: Intrusion, assault, theft in progress.\nBomb threat: Receive call, follow procedure.\nCivil disturbance: Protest, riot, mob situation.\nNatural disaster: Flooding, structural collapse.\n\nEMERGENCY RESPONSE PRINCIPLES:\nAssess before acting: What is the actual situation? Do not rush in blindly.\nProtect life first: Evacuate the area if there is danger.\nCall for help: Fire service, police, ambulance as appropriate.\nNotify management: Chain of command must be informed.\nControl the scene: Prevent unauthorised access to the incident area.\nDocument: Note time, sequence of events, actions taken.\n\nFIRE EMERGENCY:\nActivate fire alarm immediately.\nCall fire service.\nBegin controlled evacuation using designated routes.\nAccount for all persons: Roll call at muster point.\nDo not allow re-entry until fire service gives clearance.\nSmall fire with portable extinguisher: Only if you are trained, the fire is small and you have an escape route.\nPASS: Pull pin, Aim at base, Squeeze handle, Sweep side to side.\n\nMEDICAL EMERGENCY:\nCall for medical help immediately.\nDo not move the person unless in immediate danger.\nIf trained in first aid: Assess and begin appropriate first aid.\nKeep the person calm. Stay with them until medical help arrives.\nClear the area of bystanders.\n\nBOMB THREAT:\nListen carefully. Write down everything said.\nDo not touch suspected device.\nEvacuate the area.\nCall police immediately.\nKeep people away from the area.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nPractice a fire evacuation: Activate alarm, guide people to exit, account for everyone at muster point.\nRole-play a medical emergency: Assess, call for help, apply basic first aid.\nWrite an incident report for a scenario.'),
    (4, 'Report Writing and Professional Communication', 15, 'Documentation and communication are what transform a security officer into a security professional.\n\nWHY REPORTING MATTERS:\nEvidence: A well-written report is evidence in criminal or legal proceedings.\nAccountability: Demonstrates professional conduct and diligence.\nIntelligence: Patterns from reports help identify threats before they escalate.\nProtection: Protects the officer if their actions are later questioned.\n\nTHE SECURITY LOG:\nEvery post should have a log book.\nRecord: Every entry and exit. Every visitor. Every patrol. Every incident. Every communication.\nDate, time, name of officer, observation or event, action taken.\nSign every entry with full name. Never use initials only.\nDo not leave blank lines. Draw a line through blank space to prevent additions.\n\nINSTANT REPORT (for immediate incidents):\nWHO: Who was involved? Who reported it? Who responded?\nWHAT: What happened? What was said or done?\nWHEN: Exact time. Sequence of events.\nWHERE: Exact location on the premises.\nHOW: How did the incident occur? How was it resolved?\nWHY: Known or suspected cause or motive.\n\nWRITING PRINCIPLES:\nFactual: Only record what you directly observed or was directly told to you.\nObjective: No personal opinions or emotional language.\nClear: Simple, plain language. Short sentences.\nComplete: Include all relevant information.\nAccurate: Check facts before writing. Do not estimate times — if unsure, say approximately.\n\nPROFESSIONAL COMMUNICATION:\nRadio: Speak clearly. Identify yourself and your location. Keep messages brief.\nWith public: Firm, polite, respectful. Escalate firmness only when necessary.\nWith superior officers: Report accurately and concisely.\nWith emergency services: State what you need, where you are, what you know.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nWrite a complete incident report for this scenario:\nAt 22:15 on patrol, you found a broken window at the east side storage building. The window was intact on your previous patrol at 21:30. No one was seen inside. You secured the area and informed your supervisor.\nInclude all elements of the INSTANT report format.'),
    (5, 'Security Career Development', 10, 'Security is a career with real progression if you develop your skills and professionalism.\n\nCAREER LADDER:\nSecurity guard/officer: Entry level. Single site deployment.\nSenior officer: More experience, mentors junior staff.\nSupervisor: Manages a team across one or more sites.\nSite manager: Responsible for a large single site.\nOperations manager: Manages multiple sites and teams.\nSecurity consultant: Advises organisations on security strategy.\n\nSKILLS THAT ACCELERATE PROMOTION:\nFirst aid certification.\nCCTV operation and basic technical knowledge.\nFire warden certification.\nRisk assessment skills.\nDrivers licence.\nAbility to write clear, accurate reports.\nDemonstrated integrity and reliability.\n\nCERTIFICATIONS:\nMany countries have formal security officer licensing.\nSeek certification from your national private security regulatory body.\nFirst aid certification from Red Cross or similar.\nFire safety and warden certification.\n\nINTEGRITY:\nThe security profession requires absolute integrity.\nYou are trusted with access to premises, knowledge of security procedures and responsibility for safety.\nOfficers who abuse this trust face dismissal, legal consequences and damaged career.\nOfficers with proven integrity advance quickly — they are trusted with more responsibility.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nWrite your personal career plan in security:\nWhere are you now? What level do you want to reach?\nWhat skills and certifications do you need to get there?\nIn what sequence will you acquire them?\nIn what timeframe?\nThis is your security career roadmap.'),
])

add_lessons('Event Planning and Management', [
    (1, 'Introduction to Event Planning', 15, 'Event planning turns vision into reality. Every celebration, conference and ceremony needs a skilled planner.\n\nWHAT EVENT PLANNERS DO:\nConceptualise: Understand the client\'s vision and translate it into a plan.\nBudget: Plan how to achieve the vision within the available budget.\nSourcing: Identify and book all vendors, venues and services.\nCoordinate: Ensure all elements come together on the day.\nManage: Oversee the event in real-time.\nEvaluate: Review what worked and what to improve.\n\nTYPES OF EVENTS:\nSocial events: Weddings, naming ceremonies, birthday parties, graduations, funerals.\nCorporate events: Conferences, product launches, company parties, training events.\nCommunity events: Cultural festivals, charity fundraisers, sporting events.\nReligious events: Church services, mosque celebrations, crusades.\n\nEVENT PLANNING SKILLS:\nOrganisation: Tracking many details simultaneously.\nCommunication: With clients, vendors, staff and guests.\nProblem solving: Things always go wrong. Solutions matter more than perfection.\nBudgeting: Knowing where to spend and where to save.\nTime management: Strict deadlines. The event happens whether you are ready or not.\nCreativity: Making the client\'s vision come alive.\nCalmness under pressure: Events are stressful. Your calm is the team\'s calm.\n\nTHE EVENT PLANNING MARKET IN WEST AFRICA:\nCelebrations are culturally important and significant spending occasions.\nWeddings especially: Families spend generously on memorable celebrations.\nCorporate events: Growing as more businesses invest in events.\nThe market rewards planners who deliver reliably and creatively.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nAttend or volunteer at any event in your community.\nObserve: What went well? What could have been better organised?\nWho was responsible for what? How did they handle problems?\nWrite a one-page observation report.'),
    (2, 'Event Budgeting and Costing', 25, 'A realistic budget is the foundation of a successful event.\n\nEVENT BUDGET CATEGORIES:\n\nVENUE:\nHire fee. Additional hours if event overruns.\nDeposit (often 50% on booking).\nSecurity deposit (refundable if no damage).\n\nCATERING:\nFood cost per head.\nBeverages.\nService staff.\nEquipment hire (chafing dishes, crockery, cutlery).\n\nDECOR AND FLOWERS:\nFlowers, balloons, draping, centrepieces, lighting decor.\nSetup and breakdown labour.\n\nENTERTAINMENT:\nBand or DJ. MC.\nDancers, performers if applicable.\n\nFOTOGRAPHY AND VIDEO:\nPhotographer. Videographer.\nAlbum and film production.\n\nINVITATIONS AND PRINTING:\nInvitation cards. Programmes. Menus. Signage.\n\nTRANSPORT:\nClient transport. Guest shuttle if applicable.\n\nPLANNER\'S FEE:\nYour fee for organising everything.\n\nCONTINGENCY:\nAlways add 10-15% of total budget for unexpected costs.\nEvents always have unexpected costs.\n\nPRESENTING A BUDGET TO CLIENT:\nItemise every cost.\nDo not guess. Research actual prices from vendors.\nProvide three options: Basic, standard, premium.\nClients who see exactly what their money buys have fewer surprises.\nGet budget signed off in writing before booking anything.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCreate a detailed budget for a 100-person birthday party.\nContact real vendors for prices: Venue, caterer, photographer, DJ.\nPresent three budget levels: Basic, standard, premium.\nWhat is your planning fee for this event?'),
    (3, 'Vendor Management and Logistics', 25, 'An event is only as good as the vendors who deliver it.\n\nFINDING VENDORS:\nCaterers, photographers, DJs, venues, florists, decorators, rental companies.\nBuild a vendor directory: Keep contacts, prices, notes on quality.\nGet recommendations: Other event planners, satisfied clients.\nVet before using: Visit, meet in person, check their portfolio, speak to references.\n\nBOOKING VENDORS:\nAlways use written contracts.\nSpecify: Date, time, location, exactly what services are being provided, price, payment terms.\nDeposit: 30-50% to secure the date.\nCancellation policy: What happens if either party cancels?\nCheck availability first: Never promise a date to a client without confirming vendor availability.\n\nRUN-OF-SHOW DOCUMENT:\nThe master document for the event day.\nLists every element of the event in time order.\nVendor arrival times. Setup times. Guest arrival. Programme schedule.\nClear to the minute for critical moments.\nDistribute to all vendors and your team before the event.\n\nVENDOR BRIEFING:\nMeet (or call) all key vendors before the event.\nConfirm: Time of arrival. What they need (power, water, access).\nContact numbers: Ensure you can reach every vendor on the day.\nContingency: What happens if they have a problem on the day?\n\nON THE DAY:\nArrive before any vendor.\nOversee setup — check everything against specification.\nBe accessible: Vendors need to reach you.\nKeep to the run-of-show. Communicate adjustments to all affected parties.\nRemain calm: Guests should not see you stressed.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCreate a run-of-show for a 2-hour birthday party.\nTime every element from vendor arrival through to cleanup.\nIdentify all vendors and what each needs from the venue and from you.'),
    (4, 'On-The-Day Management', 20, 'The day of the event is when all preparation pays off — or problems emerge.\n\nPRE-EVENT PREPARATION:\nFinal confirmations: Call all vendors 24-48 hours before event.\nEvent kit: Running sheet, vendor contacts, scissors, tape, first aid kit, backup phone charger, safety pins, needle and thread.\nEarly arrival: Arrive at least 2-3 hours before guests.\n\nVENUE SETUP SUPERVISION:\nCheck venue is clean and set up as agreed.\nOversee decor installation — ensure it matches the agreed design.\nCheck sound and lighting.\nCheck catering setup: Correct table layout, food preparation on schedule.\nWalk the venue: Guest experience from arrival to departure.\n\nGUEST ARRIVAL:\nGreeting and reception: Someone welcoming guests.\nSeating plan if applicable: Ensure correct and accessible.\nGuest enquiries: Someone to direct and assist.\n\nDURING THE EVENT:\nFollow the run-of-show precisely. Cue each element.\nCommunicate via radio or messaging with your team.\nAnticipate: What is coming next? Is everything ready?\nProblems: Handle discreetly. Never let guests see you panicking.\nClient: Keep client informed. They should enjoy the event, not manage it.\n\nCOMMON PROBLEMS AND SOLUTIONS:\nLate vendor: Have backup contacts. Communicate to client only when you have a solution.\nFood shortage: Catering team manages portions. Never panic the room.\nTechnical failure: Have a backup for sound at minimum. DJ with phone and speaker if needed.\nWeather: Have a wet weather plan for outdoor events.\n\nPOST-EVENT:\nSupervise cleanup: Venue returned as you found it.\nCollect any equipment you brought.\nFinal payment to vendors.\nThank-you to client.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nCreate your event day checklist.\nWhat must be done before arrival? On arrival? During setup? During the event? After?\nRole-play: How would you handle a DJ who phones an hour before the event to say they cannot come?'),
    (5, 'Growing an Event Planning Business', 15, 'Event planning can grow from a side income into a highly profitable full-time business.\n\nBUSINESS STRUCTURE:\nFreelance planner: Take individual events. Lower overhead. Less stable income.\nEvent planning company: Brand, team, equipment. More stable. Higher overhead.\nStart freelance, grow into a company as client base grows.\n\nYOUR PLANNING FEE:\nTypically 10-15% of total event budget, or a flat fee per event type.\nFor a Le 5,000,000 wedding: 10% = Le 500,000 planning fee.\nFor smaller events: Flat fee approach clearer for client.\nAlways clearly define what the fee includes.\n\nSPECIALISATION:\nWeddings: Highest value but most demanding.\nCorporate: Regular repeat business from companies.\nSocial events: Wider market, typically lower budget.\nSpecialisation builds reputation faster than being a generalist.\n\nBUILDING YOUR BRAND:\nPortfolio: Photograph every event. With client permission.\nSocial media: Before-and-after transformations, event day photography.\nClient testimonials: Video testimonials are powerful.\nWord of mouth: The most powerful marketing for event planners.\nReferral partnerships: Photographers, caterers, DJs refer to planners and vice versa.\n\nSUPPLIER RELATIONSHIPS:\nYour supplier network is your competitive advantage.\nGood suppliers who give you priority, competitive pricing and loyalty.\nMaintain relationships: Recommend them. Pay promptly. Treat them professionally.\n\nPRACTICAL EXERCISE:\nDesign your event planning brand:\nBusiness name and tagline.\nServices offered and fee structure.\nTarget market (weddings? corporate? social?).\nHow will you market yourself in the first 3 months?\nThis is your event planning business plan.')
])

# Final summary
print('\n' + '='*60)
from courses.models import Course
total = 0
no_lessons = []
for c in Course.objects.all().order_by('category__pillar', 'title'):
    count = c.lessons.count()
    total += count
    if count == 0:
        no_lessons.append(f'  {c.title}')

print(f'TOTAL LESSONS: {total}')
print(f'TOTAL COURSES: {Course.objects.count()}')
if no_lessons:
    print(f'\nCourses still needing lessons ({len(no_lessons)}):')
    for c in no_lessons:
        print(c)
else:
    print('\nALL COURSES HAVE LESSONS!')